'<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p>A2.1 Repository has identified and established the duties that it needs to perform and has appointed staff with adequate skills and experience to fulfill these duties</p>','<ul> <li>&nbsp;\"The file attached here has our draft position descriptions for six job title: Research Technician - Senior...Research Area Specialist - Lead.\" (Source:<a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1387\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1387</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li> </ul> <ul> <li>\"Career Path Grid Collection Development\" Excel file (Source:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1596\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1596</a>)&nbsp; [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li> </ul> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(232,5,'A. Organizational Structure','A2. Organizational Structure &amp; Staffing','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">Organizational charts; definitions of roles and responsibilities; comparison of staffing levels to commitments and estimates of required effort.</span></p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p><h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; padding: 0px; margin: 0px;\"><strong>A2.2</strong>&nbsp;Repository has the appropriate number of staff to support all functions and services.</h3><p>&nbsp;</p>','<ul><li><span style=\"color: #494949; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">ICPSR Organizational Chart (Source:&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #027ac6; text-decoration: none;\" href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/INTRA/connection/ORGchart.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/INTRA/connection/ORGchart.pdf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</span></li><li><span style=\"color: #494949; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">534389 files delivered via Web (Source:&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #027ac6; text-decoration: none;\" href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi/INTRA/TDB/tdbrpt.prl\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi/INTRA/TDB/tdbrpt.prl</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</span></li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p><ul><li>Which staff are dedicated to long-term preservation of data?&nbsp; Is this an appropriate number given the size of long-term holdings?</li><li>Size of archived holdings to be preserved for long-term?</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(233,6,'A. Organizational Structure','A2. Organizational Structure &amp; Staffing','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">Professional development plans and reports; training requirements and training budgets, documentation of training expenditures (amount per staff); performance goals and documentation of staff assignments and achievements, copies of certificates awarded.</span></p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p><h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; padding: 0px; margin: 0px;\"><strong>A2.3</strong>&nbsp;Repository has an active professional development program in place that provides staff with skills and expertise development opportunities.</h3><p>&nbsp;</p>','<ul><li><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">ICPSR Professional Development Policy (Source:&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #027ac6; text-decoration: none;\" href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1600\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1600</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</span></li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p><ul><li>Training budget and expenditures (per staff)?</li><li>Performance goals and achievements?</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(234,7,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework',NULL,'<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3>A3.1 Repository has defined its designated community(ies) and  associated knowledge base(s) and has publicly accessible definitions  and policies in place to dictate how its preservation service  requirements will be met.</h3>','<ul><li>\"...a diverse and expanding social science research community.\" (Source: ICPSR Mission Statement; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/mission.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/mission.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>\"Develop  a strong community that consists of ICPSR members and others in the  broader world of education, science, and public policy.\" (Source: ICPSR  Strategic Plan; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/directions/direction2.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/directions/direction2.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>\"You  will need basic statistical skills for using the online analysis system  and more advanced skills for running your own analysis, although SAS,  SPSS, and Stata setup files are provided with many ICPSR datasets.\"  (Source: Data Use Tutorial; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/help/newuser.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/help/newuser.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Accessing Data web page (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/help/newuser.html#03\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/help/newuser.html#03</a>) [explaining service levels] [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Membership web page (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/membership/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/membership/index.html</a>) [explaining services for members] [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li><li>ICPSR Access Policy Framework (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/dpp-framework.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp;jsessionid=DB53F7C2E40EFE90A5712CBEF5BFA0CE</a> )</li><li>ICPSR Digital Preservation Policy Framework (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/dpp-framework.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/dpp-framework.jsp</a> )</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(235,8,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>Written documentation in the form of policies, procedures, protocols,  rules, manuals, handbooks, and workflows; specification of review cycle  for documentation; documentation detailing review, update, and  development mechanisms. If documentation is embedded in system logic,  functionality should demonstrate the implementation of policies and  procedures.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.2</strong> Repository has procedures and policies in place, and  mechanisms for their review, update, and development as the repository  grows and as technology and community practice evolve.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR Policies (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/policies/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/policies/index.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Digital Preservation Policies (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/dpp-framework.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/dpp-framework.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR Intranet (Source: <a href=\"http://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/\" target=\"_blank\">http://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Working With Data page (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/INTRA/data.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/INTRA/data.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(236,9,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>Deposit agreements; records schedule; digital preservation policies; records legislation and policies; service agreements.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.3</strong> Repository maintains written policies that specify the  nature of any legal permissions required to preserve digital content  over time, and repository can demonstrate that these permissions have  been acquired when needed.</h3>','<ul><li>\"I give my permission for the Data Collection to be used by  ICPSR for the following purposes, without limitation...to store,  translate, copy or re-format the Data Collection in any way to ensure  its future preservation and accessibility.\" (ICPSR Data Deposit Form;  Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf</span></span></a>)  [JAL, 7/20/2009] [This evidence was given before the new web site was  launched. No PDF deposit form seems to be available online as of  3/9/2010. EAM 4/13/2010.]</li></ul><ul><li>General Archive deposit form: <span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">\"I give my permission for the Data Collection to be used by ICPSR for the following purposes, without limitation: [RMC]</span></span></li></ul><blockquote>To redisseminate copies of the Data Collection in a variety of media formats<br />To promote and advertise the Data Collection in any publicity (in any form) for ICPSR<br />To describe, catalog, validate and document the Data Collection<br />To store, translate, copy or re-format the Data Collection in any way to ensure its future preservation and accessibility<br />To incorporate metadata or documentation in the Data Collection into public access catalogues\"</blockquote><ul><li><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">DataPASS deposit form: \"<span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">I  give my permission to ICPSR for the Data Collection to be used by  Data-PASS, through its Partners, for the following purposes, without  limitation: [RMC]</span></span></span></span></li></ul><blockquote>To redisseminate copies of the Data Collection in a variety of distribution formats according the standard terms of use of ICPSR<br />To promote and advertise the Data Collection in any publicity (in any form) for Data-PASS and ICPSR<br />To describe, catalog, validate and document the Data Collection<br />To store, translate, copy or re-format the Data Collection in any way to ensure its future preservation and accessibility<br />To incorporate metadata (cataloging information) or documentation in the Data Collection into public access catalogues\"</blockquote><ul><li><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</span></span></span></span>DSDR: [no section on preservation appears on test of DSDR deposit form]</li><li>CCEERC: \" \"</li><li>Robert Wood Johnson Foundation: \" \"</li><li>MDRC: \" \"</li><li>NACDA: \" \"</li><li>NACJD-BJS: \" \"</li><li style=\"margin-bottom: 3px;\">NACJD-NIJ: \"<span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">National Institute of Justice Deposit Agreement Terms . . . <span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">I  further understand that ICPSR on behalf of NIJ will describe, catalog,  validate, store, translate, copy, or reformat the Data Collection to  ensure its preservation, protection and accessibility. ICPSR will  incorporate metadata or documentation about the Data Collection into  public access catalogues, and enhance, transform and/or rearrange the  Data Collection, including the data and metadata, to the extent  supported by NIJ for the purposes of protecting respondent  confidentiality and improving usability. Finally, ICPSR, in conjunction  with NIJ will, determine the appropriate level of data protection and  access, disseminate the Data Collection in a variety of media formats,  and may promote and advertise the Data Collection in a variety of  venues.\"</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin-bottom: 3px;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">NACJD-OJJDP: [no section on preservation appears on test of deposit form]</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin-bottom: 3px;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">NAHDAP: \" \"</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin-bottom: 3px;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">PRA: \" \"</span></span></span></span></li><li style=\"margin-bottom: 3px;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"word-spacing: 0px; font: medium \'Times New Roman\'; text-transform: none; color: #000000; text-indent: 0px; white-space: normal; letter-spacing: normal; border-collapse: separate; orphans: 2; widows: 2;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 16px; font-family: \'Trebuchet MS\',Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; text-align: left;\">SAMHDA: \" \"</span></span></span></span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><em><br /></em></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',2,'Action Item(s)','<p>1. CONTENT OF THE AGREEMENTS: \"<span style=\"background-color: #ffffff; color: #800000;\">Repository   maintains written policies that specify the nature of any legal   permissions required to preserve digital content over time</span>\"</p> <ul><li>ICPSR should have a general guiding principles document for standardizing legal permissions policy. [RMC]</li><li>Consider if all deposit forms should contain at least bare minimum language. [RMC]</li><li>An  audit/clean-up of the current situation with the  deposit forms (see  evidence above) is needed. Each one should contain  minimum legal  permissions. [RMC]</li></ul> <p>2. ACCESSIBLE LOCATION OF THE AGREEMENTS: \"<span style=\"background-color: #ffffff; color: #800000;\">repository can demonstrate that these permissions have been acquired when needed.</span>\"</p> <ul><li>Currently   there is no central, easily accessible place where the legal  agreements  are kept, and where once could easily view the signed  deposit forms and  the language of the permissions statement used.  Issues: [RMC]</li></ul> <p><strong><em><br /> </em></strong></p>','<p>1. CONTENT OF THE AGREEMENTS</p> <ul><li>What   minimum information do we need in order to modify/preserve over  time?   File names, title, terms of use, who deposited it? [RMC]</li><li>The   fact that Depositors can easily by-pass the agreement should be    considered. Electronic signature is not required, as depositors can    claim it\'s on file (where? provable?), or choose other reasons not to    sign. [RMC]&nbsp;</li><li>We provide a legal policy for selected archives. [RMC]</li></ul> <p>2. ACCESSIBLE LOCATION OF THE AGREEMENTS</p> <ul><li>There are both online and hard copy deposit forms. [RMC] </li><li>Does   each agreement have the exact legal language written out, or do  they   reference versions of legal language in another form (similar to  our   codebook link to terms of use)? [RMC]</li><li>For the paper forms, where are they kept? Iron Mountain, a drawer for each archive on site, etc.? [RMC]</li><li>Can    we say we comply on all current deposit forms? What about those in  the   past? Can ICPSR produce deposit agreements for all deposits over  time?   Can we even locate deposit agreements (did they exist?) for all    deposits? Are they in Iron Mountain? Did the preservation language    change over time, under different ICPSR administrations? [RMC]</li><li>Do    the 14 entities that have deposit forms also provide PDF copies of  the   deposit form for those depositors who don\'t want to use the  electronic   version? Is that PDF version as up-to-date and identical to  the   electronic version? [RMC]</li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,1),(237,10,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>A self-assessment schedule, timetables for review and  certification; results of self-assessment; evidence of implementation of  review outcomes.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.4</strong> Repository is committed to formal, periodic review and  assessment to ensure responsiveness to technological developments and  evolving requirements.</h3>','<ul><li>\"ICPSR is committed to a two-year cycle of self-assessment and a  five-year audit cycle to evaluate, measure, and adjust the policies,  procedures, preservation approaches, and practices of the digital  preservation function.\" (Source: ICPSR Digital Preservation Policy  Framework; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/dpp-framework.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/dpp-framework.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>Evidence of regular or periodic review? </li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(238,11,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>A policy that requires a feedback mechanism; a procedure that addresses  how the repository seeks, captures, and documents responses to feedback;  documentation of workflow for feedback (i.e., how feedback is used and  managed); quality assurance records.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.5</strong> Repository has policies and procedures to ensure that feedback from producers and users is sought and addressed over time.</h3>','<ul><li>\"Implement a system to continuously monitor users\' and members\'  data needs, current use of/interaction with ICPSR resources, and needs  and desires for future use/interaction\" (ICPSR Strategic Plan, Direction  2: Membership Value, Strategy B, Objective 1; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/directions/direction2.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/directions/direction2.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>\"Schedule  periodic gatherings of various customer segments for the purpose of  exploring evolving needs, identifying challenges to use of ICPSR  resources, and generating new ideas for use.\" (ICPSR Strategic Plan,  Direction 2: Membership Value, Strategy B, Objective 3; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/directions/direction2.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/directions/direction2.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li><li>The  Web site has a feedback form that appears at the base of each page that  enables users to submit feedback regarding site errors/content issues. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/report-problem.jsp?url=http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/report-problem.jsp?url=http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/index.jsp</a>&nbsp;[MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>The error pages and the \'no search results found\' pages include email address for Web support and User support. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies?archive=ICPSR&amp;q=genome+data\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies?archive=ICPSR&amp;q=genome+data</a>[MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>The  Web site provides contact information on its Web site, as well as  detailed staff information, including email addresses and phone numbers.  <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/contact.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/contact.jsp</a>[MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>ICPSR  maintains a ticketing system so that feedback sent to  web-support@icps.umich.edu or netmail@icpsr.umich.edu is logged and  reviewed. Feedback that arrives outside those channels is routinely  added into the ticketing system so that it can be tracked. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/shared/ICPSR/help/index\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/shared/ICPSR/help/index</a>&nbsp;[MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>Every  two years, the Web team initiates the re-design process by soliciting  feedback from ICPSR staff, managers, and site users, via email to all  staff, OR-Announce, ICPSR-Announce, and posts on the Web site. That  feedback is reviewed and prioritized to determine how we will improve  the Web site as part of the re-design. <a href=\"http://icpsr.blogspot.com/2009_08_01_archive.html\">http://icpsr.blogspot.com/2009_08_01_archive.html</a>[MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>When  preparing a re-design for the topical archives, the Web team meets with  the archive manager to determine what should be included with the  re-design. Unlike ICPSR, it is the responsibility of the archive manager  to solicit feedback from the funding agency. [MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>Staff  suggestions are logged either in JIRA (for small tasks) or in the  Project Tracking System (for larger projects) where they are  evaluated/prioritized by the appropriate committees. [MR, 2/16/2010]</li><li>The  Web team is in the process of building a system whereby every site  manager meets with a Web developer once every six months to discuss  broadly how well the site is performing its task and how it might be  improved. This system should be in place for FY2010-2011. [MR,  2/16/2010]</li><li>Periodic surveys of the members solicit suggestions for new data and feedback on ICPSR resources and services. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/files/ICPSR/or/2010ORResearchReport.pptx\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/files/ICPSR/or/2010ORResearchReport.pptx</a>[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>Biennial meetings of the members solicit suggestions for new data and feedback on ICPSR resources and services. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/or/ormeet/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/or/ormeet/index.jsp</a>[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR and its topical archives attend conferences where attendees get feedback on ICPSR resources and services. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/publications/index.jsp;jsessionid=B05716313CB3045FDFB13545B9AD82FB\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/publications/index.jsp;jsessionid=B05716313CB3045FDFB13545B9AD82FB</a>[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR  staff are in contact with data producers before Ingest and throughout  the Ingest process until data are released. During this time feedback  can be elicited. [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>Council meets with  staff three times a year to provide guidance and feedback. Action items  are recorded and acted upon, usually by the time of the next Council  meeting. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/governance/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/governance/index.jsp</a>[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR has a form on the Web site for users to suggest new data to archive. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit/suggest.jsp?source=deposit\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit/suggest.jsp?source=deposit</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR  reviews and monitors a database of grants awarded by major funders  (NSF, NIH) to understand trends in research and to identify data that  should be archived. [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>Outcomes from Marketing on contacting users (e.g., survey results, reports)? </li><li>Is a survey of data depositors and the deposit experience needed?</li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(239,12,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>Policies, procedures, and results of changes that affect all levels of  the repository: objects, aggregations of objects; object-level  preservation metadata; repository\'s records retention strategy document.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.6</strong> Repository has a documented history of the changes to  its operations, procedures, software, and hardware that, where  appropriate, is linked to relevant preservation strategies and describes  potential effects on preserving digital content.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>&nbsp;Does Mike Shove\'s system do this?</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(240,13,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>Comprehensive documentation that is readily accessible to stakeholders;  unhindered access to content and associated information within  repository.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.7</strong> Repository commits to transparency and accountability in  all actions supporting the operation and management of the repository,  especially those that affect the preservation of digital content over  time.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR Strategic Plan (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/strategic/index.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR Organization and Governance web page (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/governance/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/governance/index.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR Annual Reports (Source: <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.3886/ICPSR04006\" target=\"_blank\">http://dx.doi.org/10.3886/ICPSR04006</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR Council web page (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/council/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/council/</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Digital Preservation Policies and Planning at ICPSR (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR-Managed Email Lists (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/lists/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/org/lists/index.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>The ICPSR Blog (Source: <a href=\"http://community.livejournal.com/ormeeting\" target=\"_blank\">http://community.livejournal.com/ormeeting</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR Official Representative Site (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/or/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/or/</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR\'s YouTube Channel (Source: <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/user/ICPSRWeb\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/user/ICPSRWeb</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR\'s Twitter account (Source: <a href=\"http://twitter.com/ICPSR\" target=\"_blank\">http://twitter.com/ICPSR</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR on Facebook (Source: <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/ICPSR/43191688396\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.facebook.com/pages/ICPSR/43191688396</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>Specific digital preservation documentation? </li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(241,14,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>An implemented registry system; a definition of the repository\'s  integrity measurements; documentation of the procedures and mechanisms  for integrity measurements; an audit system for collecting, tracking,  and presenting integrity measurements; procedures for responding to  results of integrity measurements that indicate digital content is at  risk; policy and workflow documentation.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.8</strong> Repository commits to defining, collecting, tracking, and providing, on demand, its information integrity measurements.</h3>','<ul><li>MD5 Checksum upon acquisition [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Deposit Viewer (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi/INTRA/data/dview\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi/INTRA/data/dview</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Study Tracking System (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/INTRA/sts\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/INTRA/sts</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Audit &amp; Control Working Group (Source: <a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1409\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1409</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',1,'Evidence Proposed','<ul><li>Audit system for collecting, tracking, presenting, and responding to integrity measurements? </li></ul>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(242,15,'A. Organizational Structure','A3. Procedural Accountability &amp; Policy Framework','<p>Completed, dated audit checklists from self-assessment or objective  audit; certificates awarded for certification; presence in a  certification register (when available); timetable or budget allocation  for future certification.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A3.9</strong> Repository commits to a regular schedule of  self-assessment and certification and, if certified, commits to  notifying certifying bodies of operational changes that will change or  nullify its certification status.</h3>','<ul><li>Audit &amp; Control Working Group (Source: <a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1409\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1409</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>\"ICPSR  is committed to a two-year cycle of self-assessment and a five-year  audit cycle to evaluate, measure, and adjust the policies, procedures,  preservation approaches, and practices of the digital preservation  function.\" (ICPSR Digital Preservation Policy Framework; Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/dpp-framework.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DP/policies/dpp-framework.html</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>CRL Audit of ICPSR in 2006 (Source: <a href=\"http://www.crl.edu/PDF/ICPSR_final.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.crl.edu/PDF/ICPSR_final.pdf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>Can we join or establish a pool of organizations ready to be audited? </li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(243,16,'A. Organizational Structure','A4. Financial Sustainability','<p>Operating plans; financial reports; budgets; financial audit reports;  annual financial reports; financial forecasts; business plans; audit  procedures and calendars; evidence of comparable institutions; exposure  of business plan to scenarios.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A4.1</strong> Repository has short- and long-term business planning processes in place to sustain the repository over time.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(244,17,'A. Organizational Structure','A4. Financial Sustainability','<p>Business plans, audit planning (e.g., scope, schedule, process, and  requirements) and results; financial forecasts; recent audits and  evidence of impact on repository operating procedures.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A4.2</strong> Repository has in place processes to review and adjust business plans at least annually.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(245,18,'A. Organizational Structure','A4. Financial Sustainability','<p>Demonstrated dissemination requirements for business planning and  practices; citations to and/or examples of accounting and audit  requirements, standards, and practice; evidence of financial audits  already taking place.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A4.3</strong> Repository\'s financial practices and procedures are  transparent, compliant with relevant accounting standards and practices,  and audited by third parties in accordance with territorial legal  requirements.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(246,19,'A. Organizational Structure','A4. Financial Sustainability','<p>Risk management documents that identify perceived and potential threats  and planned or implemented responses (a risk register); technology  infrastructure investment planning documents; costbenefit analyses;  financial investment documents and portfolios; requirements for and  examples of licenses, contracts, and asset management; evidence of  revision based on risk.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A4.4</strong> Repository has ongoing commitment to analyze and report  on risk, benefit, investment, and expenditure (including assets,  licenses, and liabilities).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(247,20,'A. Organizational Structure','A4. Financial Sustainability','<p>Fiscal and fiduciary policies, procedures, protocols, requirements; budgets and financial analysis documents; fiscal calendars; business plan(s); any evidence of active monitoring and preparedness.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A4.5</strong> Repository commits to monitoring for and bridging gaps in funding.</h3>','<p>ICPSR maintains a reserve to cover six months of operational expenses should there be a gap in funding and this reserve is well-documented in the budgetary documents produced three times per year for review by the ICPSR Council and in documents that support ICPSR\'s <em>Annual Report <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/publications/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/org/publications/index.jsp</a></em></p><p>The existing reserve should cover most gaps and allow ICPSR time to identify additional sources of funding.&nbsp;</p><p>[Digital Preservation, 23 March 2011]</p>',3,'Evidence Reviewed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(248,21,'A. Organizational Structure','A5. Contracts, Licenses, &amp; Liabilities','<p>Deposit agreements; policies on third-party deposit arrangements;  contracts; definitions of service levels; Web archiving policies;  procedure for reviewing and maintaining agreements, contracts, and  licenses.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A5.1</strong> If repository manages, preserves, and/or provides access  to digital materials on behalf of another organization, it has and  maintains appropriate contracts or deposit agreements.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR Data Deposit Form and Agreement (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed','<ul><li>A project has been opened with CNS to address some of these issues. See:   https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/2202. </li></ul>','<ul><li>Deposit agreements specify rights, responsibilities, and expectations.&nbsp;  However, ICPSR\'s procedures to store and maintain contracts, including  the specific language agreed upon at time of signature, is not  formalized. Questions remain about: Where in the database are individual  and institutional contracts kept?&nbsp; What are procedures for transferring  contract if different archive processes data collection?&nbsp; Where are  hard copy agreements kept?&nbsp; Does ICPSR appropriately collect the  electronic signature?&nbsp; If staff indicates that the deposit signature is  on file or on contract, there currently isn\'t indication where one could  go to locate the file. </li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,1),(249,22,'A. Organizational Structure','A5. Contracts, Licenses, &amp; Liabilities','<p>Contracts, deposit agreements; specification(s) of rights transferred  for different types of digital content (if applicable); policy statement  on requisite preservation rights.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A5.2</strong> Repository contracts or deposit agreements must specify  and transfer all necessary preservation rights, and those rights  transferred must be documented.</h3>','<ul><li>\"I give my permission for the Data Collection to be used by ICPSR for  the following purposes, without limitation....To store, translate, copy  or re-format the Data Collection in any way to ensure its future  preservation and accessibility.\" (ICPSR Data Deposit Form; Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>ICPSR revised it\'s deposit agreement language around 3 years ago.&nbsp; The  deposit agreement clearly specifies the terms of the transfer and  informs the depositor that they are giving ICPSR rights to modify,&nbsp;  store and share a copy of their research data.&nbsp; A couple a questions  about the deposit agreement remain.&nbsp; 1) It is unclear that ICPSR is  exceuting the electronic signature properly. 2) It is unclear what  process the various archives at ICPSR may use to amend (and document)  the deposit terms.&nbsp; 3) It is not clear when it is appropriate for ICPSR  staff to \"sign\" the deposit agreement in lieu of the data creator. 4)  Copyrighted materials (e.g. survey instrument) are deposited using the  same deposit terms.</li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(250,23,'A. Organizational Structure','A5. Contracts, Licenses, &amp; Liabilities','<p>Submission agreements/deposit agreements/deeds of gift; written standard operating procedures.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A5.3</strong> Repository has specified all appropriate aspects of  acquisition, maintenance, access, and withdrawal in written agreements  with depositors and other relevant parties.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR Data Deposit Form and Agreement (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>DSDR Designing a Restricted Data Use Contract web pages (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DSDR/rduc/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DSDR/rduc/</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(251,24,'A. Organizational Structure','A5. Contracts, Licenses, &amp; Liabilities','<p>A policy statement that defines and specifies the repository\'s  requirements and process for managing intellectual property rights;  depositor agreements; samples of agreements and other documents that  specify and address intellectual property rights; demonstrable way to  monitor intellectual property; results from monitoring.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A5.4</strong> Repository tracks and manages intellectual property  rights and restrictions on use of repository content as required by  deposit agreement, contract, or license.</h3>','<ul><li>\"After both ICPSR and a responsible official at the researcher\'s  institution sign [a restricted use agreement], a copy of the data is  sent on CD-ROM via registered mail directly to the researcher. The  agreement requires the applicant to destroy the data after a set period  of time and to provide ICPSR with proof that the data have been  destroyed.\" (Source:  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.html) [JAL,  7/20/2009]</li><li>There is a full time staff position that is responsible for managing and tracking restricted-use agreements. [RMC]</li><li>\"According to the OAIS Reference Model:<br />Digital  SIPs may be delivered via electronic transfer (e.g., FTP), loaded from  media submitted to the archive, or simply mounted (e.g., CD-ROM) on the  archive file system for access. Non-digital SIPs would likely be  delivered by conventional shipping procedures. The Receive Submission  function may represent a legal transfer of custody for the Content  Information in the SIP, and may require that special access controls be  placed on the contents. This function provides a confirmation of receipt  of a SIP to the Producer, which may include a request to resubmit a SIP  in the case of errors resulting from the SIP submission.\" (Source:  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/receipt.jsp) [RMC]</li><li>&nbsp;\"Users  who wish to redistribute data or include them in a new data product or  service must receive permission from ICPSR. These are the criteria that  ICPSR considers when reviewing redistribution proposals:</li></ul><blockquote>Will the product benefit the research community?<br />Does the proposed product offer functionality not available from ICPSR?<br />Does it benefit the ICPSR membership?<br />Will the proposed license agreement be acceptable to the ICPSR membership?<br />Will the proposed remuneration to ICPSR be satisfactory?\"</blockquote><blockquote>(Source: ICPSR Access and Dissemination: http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/dissemination.jsp) [RMC]</blockquote><ul><li>Receipt  of Submission: When the negotiation between a data producer and a  repository results in a submission of content to the repository, there  must be checks in place to validate and process the submission. Secure  handling of the submission is also critical. Many repositories establish  an accession register that tracks all submissions and identifies them  uniquely.\" (Source:ICPSR Restricted data:  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp)  [RMC] **NOTE** Language no longer appears at this URL [EB 01/13/11]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">How are restricted data monitored?&nbsp; Tracking system? [RMC]</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Are non-confidential member-only data monitored? [RMC]</span></li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(252,25,'A. Organizational Structure','A5. Contracts, Licenses, &amp; Liabilities','<p>A definition of rights; citations for relevant laws and requirements;  policy on responding to challenges; documented track record for  responding to challenges in ways that do not inhibit preservation;  examples of legal advice sought and received.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>A5.5</strong> If repository ingests digital content with unclear  ownership/rights, policies are in place to address liability and  challenges to those rights.</h3>','<ul><li>Although ICPSR may not have a documented track record of responding to   challenges based on unclear ownership, as part of the University of   Michigan, it has access to the University Counsel\'s Office. Data Deposit   and Transfer forms are vetted by this office before becoming ICPSR   policy. [RMC]&nbsp; </li></ul>',NULL,'Action Item(s)','<p>1) The emphasis in deposit form, Terms of Use, and  restricted data  form are so clearly on liability for breaches of  confidentiality or  invasions of privacy, that both forms could use a  list of the rights  being transferred, those retained by the depositor,  and any held by  ICPSR that are not transferred to users.&nbsp; If a list  risks limiting our  rights, a general reference would work instead. [RMC]</p><p>2)  In data  collected under a Federal contract (e.g., by NACJD, SAMDHA, and  other  relevant topical archives), the contract between the data producer  and  the funding agency should be made a part of the study  documentation.  [RMC]</p>','<p>ICPSR does not knowingly ingest digital content with unclear  ownership.&nbsp; It protects against this by making acquisition dependent on  the depositor\'s signing a statement that s/he has the right to make&nbsp; the  data publicly available through ICPSR.&nbsp; [Evidence -- Data Deposit  forms, specifically the following language.&nbsp; ICPSR requires \"your  electronic signature attesting to the following statement[s]: I have  implicit or explicit copyright to this work and have the right to make  it publicly available <br />through ICPSR.\"] [RMC]</p><p>Studies are  sometimes submitted under contract (or InterAgency Agreement) with a  Federal agency.&nbsp; The archive\'s practice has been to assume that the  contract is sufficient proof of the funder\'s rights over the data. Such  data comes under the Federal Acquisitions Regulations (FAR), under which  \"the Government has unlimited rights in all data first produced in the  performance of a contract and all data delivered under a contract unless  provided otherwise in the contract.\" There are circumstances in which  the researcher retains copyright, but in those cases \"the Government,  and others acting on its behalf, are granted a license to reproduce,  prepare derivative works, distribute, perform and display the  copyrighted work.\"&nbsp; See <a href=\"http://www.cendi.gov/publications/04-8copyright.html#41\">http://www.cendi.gov/publications/04-8copyright.html#41</a> for a summary of FAR. [RMC]</p><p>ICPSR  does have experience with researchers who wish to withdraw data, and at  least one of these situations was precipitated by unclear ownership.  The following examples are paraphrased from an email from Erik Austin,  retired Assistant Director of ICPSR.&nbsp; A PI had not cleared deposit of  the data with a co-PI; the latter eventually agreed to leave the data  with ICPSR.&nbsp; In another example, the researcher had fogotten that he had  deposited the data.&nbsp; A copy of the permission form with his signature  was sufficient to clear up the misunderstanding.&nbsp; Related examples  include instances where the researcher disapproved of something done to  the data in processing.&nbsp; [RMC]</p><p>The general practice has been to  negotiate with the researcher, attempting to explain ICPSR\'s actions and  convince him/her of their value. However, the archive\'s overriding  practice has been to accept the researcher\'s decision, since she/he  remains the true owner of the data. The one exception to this would be  where the research is the product of a grant under the terms of which  the granting agency retains ownership, see point 2 above. [RMC]</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,1),(253,26,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Mission statement; submission agreements/deposit agreements/deeds of  gift; workflow and policy documents, including written definition of  properties as agreed in the deposit agreement/deed of gift; written  processing procedures; documentation of properties to be preserved.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.1</strong> Repository identifies properties it will preserve for digital objects.</h3>',NULL,1,'Not Done',NULL,'<ul><li>Nowhere do we explicitly state what we will and will not preserve.&nbsp; </li></ul> <p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/03/trac-b11-what-we-preserve.html [BB 4/11/2010]:</p> <p>\"My  sense is that this TRAC requirement is more about policy than  technology, but nonetheless I\'ll comment on it from a status quo,  technological standpoint for the purposes of this post. That will give  the reader a good sense for how things are working today, but leaves  open the possibility (likelihood?) that ICPSR may change its mission  statement, submission agreements, and/or other possibilities down the  road, and then the underlying technology will change too.<br /><br />The  short version of the story is that ICPSR captures two essential items  from each submission: the data (normalized into plain ASCII characters),  and the technical documentation (normalized into DDI XML, PDF, and TIF  images). And we keep the content in these formats until we need to  migrate to a different format.<br /><br />In our world of survey research  data there is no requirement to preserve original formats (such as a SAS  Portable file), look and feel (such as original technical documentation  written in Word Perfect), or even low-level data format (such as  numeric data coded in punched card format). We can take everything, pull  out the essential intellectual content, and then normalize that content  in quite durable formats.<br /><br />That said, we may take these durable  formats, such as DDI XML metadata and plain ASCII data, and feed them  into tools that produce dissemination formats that are easier for our  designated community to use. This includes common stat package formats,  and also includes formats that feed into our on-line analysis system.  However, these dissemination formats are not preserved, and they contain  no essential properties not also contained in the preservation formats.<br /><br />As  I\'ve been thinking about this particular TRAC requirement over the past  week, I think we\'re probably missing one important piece of information  for each of our data files: the character set. In practice almost all  of our holdings are numeric data, and so our implicit character set  (\"us-ascii\") is the correct one to use, but this seems like a good area  for being more explicit. This would allow us to handle data files that  contain non-numeric, non-US-ASCII characters in a more durable  fashion.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(254,27,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Transfer requirements; producer-archive agreements.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.2</strong> Repository clearly specifies the information that needs  to be associated with digital material at the time of its deposit (i.e.,  SIP).</h3>','<ul><li>\"Here you may upload all files relevant to your deposit....Specifically,  please upload: Data - ICPSR prefers to receive data files in SPSS, SAS  or Stata formats.&nbsp; Documentation - ICPSR prefers to receive electronic  documentation in formats such as ASCII (text files) or Microsoft Word.  The original source document is preferred, but PDF files are  acceptable.\" (VI. Upload Files section of the ICPSR Data Deposit Form;  Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf</a>)  [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>While the Data Deposit Form captures metadata about a study, only  one field is required (PI name) and documentation is optional.</li></ul><p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/08/trac-b12-defining-deposit-requirements.html [BB 8/27/2010]:</p><p>\"ICPSR  is pretty flexible with regard to its deposit requirements. The  business rules behind our Deposit Form web app allow one to submit  content for deposit at ICPSR with little more than a working title for  the deposit and a signature. Of course, the Deposit Form also has many,  many fields for collecting additional descriptive metadata, but those  fields are not required (although we do appreciate all of the  descriptive metadata we can get).<br /><br />On the back-end of the deposit  our business rules require us to create, collect, and store the  following information about each file in the deposit:<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. Original name from the deposit<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. MIME type<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 3. Unique ID (that we create and assign)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 4. Fingerprint and the method used to collect the fingerprint (currently MD5 hashes)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 5. Date of deposit<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 6. Location<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 7. Identity of the depositor<br /><br />All  of this information is available to ICPSR data managers through a web  app called the Deposit Viewer. This is a bit of a misnomer, however, and  a more appropriate name for the web app would be the Deposit Manager  since it allows data managers to take actions on the deposit, such as  changing its status, or downloading the files which were deposited.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(255,28,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Submission agreements/deposit agreements/deeds of gift; workflow  documents; evidence of appropriate technological measures; logs from  procedures and authentications.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p>B1.3 Repository has mechanisms to authenticate the source of all materials</p>','<p><strong>Submissions using Online Deposit Form </strong></p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">ICPSR Data Deposit Form:<span>&nbsp; </span>Deposits are made using this secure form to describe the data collection and upload content. (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009].<span>&nbsp; </span></span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Depositors must have a <a href=\"https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/mydata?path=ICPSR\">MyData Account</a> to submit materials to ICPSR via the deposit form.<span>&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">MyData  is the user registration and authentication system for the ICPSR Web  site. The system creates a more secure environment for users and enables  them to sign up for services that ICPSR is developing. MyData has the  following user-friendly features:</span></li></ul> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1in; text-indent: -0.25in; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Courier New\';\"><span>o<span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Uses an email address as a login ID</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1in; text-indent: -0.25in; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Courier New\';\"><span>o<span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Requires a password to authenticate to the Web site</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1in; text-indent: -0.25in; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Courier New\';\"><span>o<span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Allows users to create an account and set preferences</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1in; text-indent: -0.25in; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Courier New\';\"><span>o<span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Allows registered users to reset a forgotten password</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1in; text-indent: -0.25in; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Courier New\';\"><span>o<span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Enables users to view prior download history</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1in; text-indent: -0.25in; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Courier New\';\"><span>o<span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Enables  users to subscribe to an update notification service that emails users  when a study they\'ve previously downloaded is substantially updated</span></p> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Data Deposit Verification:<span>&nbsp; </span>ICPSR  sends an automatically generated message in response to files that  person(s) uploaded to ICPSR through the online deposit form.<span>&nbsp; </span>This includes a listing of the files received and a description of the format of the files uploaded as detected by our software.<span>&nbsp; </span>If data are deposited in SAS, SPSS, or Stata formats, we provide a count of cases and variables in each data file.<span>&nbsp; </span>[JR 5/14/2010].</span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Data Producer Feedback:<span>&nbsp; </span>Depositors  who use the online deposit form are asked to review the listing of  files carefully to be sure that it corresponds to what they intended to  submit to ICPSR and to contact us with any discrepancies or questions  [JR 5/14/2010].</span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">ICPSR Deposit Viewer:<span>&nbsp; </span>an ICPSR Intranet web page that lets you track materials that depositors have submitted to ICPSR.<span>&nbsp; </span>(Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi/INTRA/data/dview\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi/INTRA/data/dview</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Downloaded Data :<span>&nbsp; </span>Some of ICPSR’s data is obtained by directly downloading from the data producer’s website.<span>&nbsp; </span>These  collections are reviewed/verified by the archive manager and/or data  processor to ensure that the files match the documentation (e.g.  variable and case counts) with follow up to the data producer as needed  [JR 5/14/2010] .</span></li></ul> <p><strong>Submissions via Mail </strong></p> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Symbol;\"><span><span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\"> </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Data on CD/DVD:<span>&nbsp; </span>ICPSR accepts data deposits on CD/DVD via standard mail and UPS, FedEx, etc. (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0086\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0086</a> [JR 5/14/2010].</span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">ICPSR ‘chkdep’ procedure:<span>&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">chkdep  is a program that compares all of the digital content on a removable  media with the files in the deposit directory that is associated with  the data deposit.<span>&nbsp; </span><span>&nbsp;</span>Processors work with data producers to resolve any discrepancies as needed <span>&nbsp;</span>[JR 5/14/2010]</span></li></ul> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 0.25in;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">&nbsp;</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 0in;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">Additional Evidence </span></strong></p> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Symbol;\"><span><span style=\"font: 7pt \'Times New Roman\';\"> </span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">MD5 checksums attached to files [JAL, 7/20/2009]</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\"> - While material can be verified through visual comparison with deposit  information, no internal md5 checksum is in place to ensure uncorrupted  file transfer.</span></li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',\'serif\';\">ICPSR  staff have the ability to sign on behalf of depositors, when  appropriate, in instances where ICPSR has an established  relationship/history with the data producer (e.g. a deposit for a new  wave of a longitudinal study). [JR 5/14/2010].</span></p>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>While material can be verified through visual comparison with deposit  information, no internal md5 checksum is in place to ensure uncorrupted  file transfer.</li></ul><ul><li>There is no verification procedure for MyData accounts.</li></ul><ul><li>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/09/trac-b13-authenticating-source.html [BB 9/3/2010]:</li></ul><ul><li>\"ICPSR\'s <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\">Deposit Form</a> &nbsp; is the mechanism that ensures proper documentation and workflow for  deposited materials. It ensures that we have a signature from the data  depositor, and keeps track of what was deposited, who did it, and when  it was done.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>One feature of the Deposit Form is that it  auto-emails the depositor with a list of the files it thinks have been  deposited, and each file includes a one-line description regarding the  file format (e.g., SPSS Portable File, PDF document, version 1.6, or  Microsoft Word). If the deposited file is a Zip package or a tarball, we  pull apart the bundle first, and then examine the individual files  before generating this report.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>The person who signs the deposit  must have a valid MyData account, and we use this to track and record  identity. Of course, this same information is also helpful during the  data management process if ICPSR needs to contact the data producer or  researcher.\"</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(256,29,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Appropriate policy documents and system log files from system performing  ingest procedure; formal or informal acquisitions register of files  received during the transfer and ingest process; workflow, documentation  of standard operating procedures, detailed procedures; definition of  completeness and correctness, probably incorporated in policy documents.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.4</strong> Repository\'s ingest process verifies each submitted object (i.e., SIP) for completeness and correctness as specified in B1.2.</h3>','<ul><li>Review and Submit page of the ICPSR Data Deposit Form (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>E-mail  message to depositors: \"This message is automatically generated in  response to files you (or your group) uploaded to ICPSR through the  online deposit form.&nbsp; When ICPSR receives files through the data deposit  form, we automatically generate a listing of the files received.&nbsp; This  list also includes a description of the format of the files uploaded as  detected by our software.&nbsp; And for data deposited in SAS, SPSS, or Stata  formats, we provide a count of cases and variables in each data file.&nbsp;  Please review the following information carefully to be sure that it  corresponds to what you intended to submit to ICPSR.&nbsp; Please contact us  with any discrepancies or questions that you have  (deposit@icpsr.umich.edu)....CW-Wave2.sav was scanned on 30-JUN-09.&nbsp; We  think it\'s: SPSS System File MS Windows 16.0.2\" (\"ICPSR Acknowledgement  and Inventory of Files Deposited\" Email) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<ul><li>ICPSR provides an approximate verification of each submitted item, although exact verification is not available. </li></ul><ul><li>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/09/trac-b14-checking-completeness-and.html [BB 9/10/2010]:</li></ul><ul><li>\"For  this post I am going to focus on the files that a depositor uploads to  our web site. The other elements of the deposit, which are largely  metadata, are collected automatically by the deposit system. It\'s only a  title or name for the deposit that the depositor must provide.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>As  mentioned in an early post on deposits, we collect several pieces of  information about each file. One item we collect is the MIME type, and  we do this using the UNIX file utility, but where we have expanded the  magic database to include information about common statistical packages  and Microsoft Office file formats. For example, a vanilla,  out-of-the-box version of file will report a DOCX format file as a Zip  file, and while that is correct on some level, it wasn\'t the best  description of the file.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>After making this inventory, our system  generates an auto-reply to the depositor enumerating the files and what  we think they are. Note that we do not assign any higher level purpose  (e.g., this is a data file; this is a codebook) programatically.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Assuming  that the depositor does not find anything amiss with our inventory, a  data manager will pick up the deposit, and will start preparing the  materials for preservation at ICPSR, and for distribution on our web  site.</li></ul><ul><li>A couple of things we are NOT doing, but which might be valuable in the future....</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>One,  in addition to using file to report MIME types, we might also run a  tool like JHOVE to inspect the correctness of the file formats. We do  get a fair number of PDF format documents, and JHOVE does a nice job  with those. However, we also get a lot of plain text documents, stats  files, and MS Office files, and JHOVE doesn\'t do a very nice job with  those. I\'ve wondered if we might be able to write a small grant where  ICPSR would promise to build plug-ins for JHOVE for the stats package  formats.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Two, in addition to reporting file formats to our  depositors, we might also report checksums for each file so that they  would have the opportunity to inspect that the deposit went without  error.\" </li></ul>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(257,30,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Submission agreements/deposit agreements/deeds of gift; workflow  documents; system log files from the system performing ingest  procedures; logs of files captured during Web harvesting.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.5</strong> Repository obtains sufficient physical control over the digital objects to preserve them.</h3>','<ul><li>\"...the data deposit form grants permission for ICPSR to archive and  distribute your data collection.\" (ICPSR Data Deposit Form; Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed','<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/09/trac-b15-gaining-control-of-deposits.html [BB 9/17/2010]:</p><p>\"This  requirement is fairly straight-forward for ICPSR, given the type of  content that we collect and curate. We gain complete control of the  entire deposit, including both the research data and documentation. The  deposit may also contain core related materials like the questionnaire  that was used to collect the data.<br /><br />That said, a deposit may be  related to other objects outside the scope of ICPSR, such as  publications related to the data. In this case ICPSR is not expecting to  find such content in the deposit, nor would we tend to curate it even  if it was present.\"&nbsp;</p>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(258,31,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Submission agreements/deposit agreements/deeds of gift; workflow  documentation; standard operating procedures; evidence of reporting  back.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.6</strong> Repository provides producer/depositor with appropriate responses at predefined points during the ingest processes.</h3>','<ul><li>Deposit e-mails [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed','<ul><li>Listing of all auto-generated e-mails distributed by ICPSR during ingest process? </li></ul><ul><li>&nbsp;From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/09/trac-b16-communicating-with-depositors.html [BB 9/24/2010]:</li></ul><p>\"ICPSR updates the depositor during the ingest process at two main points.<br /><br />One,  after the deposit is signed, ICPSR generates an inventory of the  deposited content, and communicates this via email. This gives the  depositor the opportunity to identify any content that was uploaded  unintentionally or that may have become corrupted. These inventory  reports are generated automatically by the deposit system.<br /><br />Two,  if deposited material is later used to produce an ICPSR study, the  depositor is notified when that study is made available on ICPSR\'s web  site, and when a normalized version of the content is moved into  archival storage.&nbsp; \"</p>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(259,32,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Submission agreements/deposit agreements/deeds of gift; confirmation receipt sent back to producer.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.7</strong> Repository can demonstrate when preservation  responsibility is formally accepted for the contents of the submitted  data objects (i.e., SIPs).</h3>','<ul><li>\"...the data deposit form grants permission for ICPSR to archive and  distribute your data collection.\" (ICPSR Data Deposit Form; Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/ICPSR/access/deposit/data-deposit-form.pdf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed','<ul><li>While overall preservation is made explicit upon transfer, and  although a file listing of all uploaded files is returned to the  depositor, no confirmation is provided confirming which files will be  preserved.&nbsp; The tacit message is that everything will be preserved. </li></ul><ul><li>No consistent file listing is provided for deposits made outside the online data deposit form. </li></ul><ul><li>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/10/trac-b17-formal-acceptance-of-deposits.html [BB 10/1/2010]:</li></ul><p>\"My sense is that this requirement has two very different stories at ICPSR.<br /><br />One  story is pretty simple.&nbsp; When the depositor signs his/her deposit,  custody transfers to ICPSR.&nbsp; We then work the deposit until we have a  post-processed version suitable for digital preservation and versions  suitable for delivery on the web site.<br /><br />The other story is more  complicated.&nbsp; The workflow allows one to un-sign a deposit.&nbsp; And so the  custody of the object could transfer from the depositor to ICPSR (at the  initial signing), and then back to the depositor (upon un-signing).&nbsp;  This can even happen in a case where the deposit has been processed and  released on the ICPSR web site.&nbsp; The workflow records this sort of  action, and so it is well documented, but does leave open a degenerate  case where content is available on the web without the corresponding  original submission in archival storage.\"&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(260,33,'B. Digital Object Management','B1. Ingest: Acquisition of Content','<p>Written documentation of decisions and/or action taken; preservation  metadata logged, stored, and linked to pertinent digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B1.8</strong> Repository has contemporaneous records of actions and  administration processes that are relevant to preservation (Ingest:  content acquisition).</h3>','<ul><li>Processing History files [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul><ul><li>Metadata records [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',1,'Evidence Proposed','<ul><li>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/10/trac-b18-ingest-records.html [BB 10/8/2010]:</li></ul><p>\"ICPSR\'s  main business process is to take deposited materials (usually studies)  and prepare them for preservation and dissemination (also as studies).&nbsp;  We use two internal webapps to collect, display, and set milestones and  records during this process.<br /><br />One system is called the Deposit  Viewer, although it might be more properly called the Deposit Manager.&nbsp;  ICPSR staff use it to change the status of a deposit, assign a deposit  to a worker, to read or create metadata about the deposit, and to link  deposits to studies.&nbsp; This system also allows staff (and sometimes  requires them) to make comments in a diary associated with the deposit.<br /><br />The  other system is called the Study Tracking System, and like the Deposit  Viewer, it collects milestones and diary entries during the ingest  lifecycle.<br /><br />The records are stored in a relational database.&nbsp; This  ensures that the content is readily available to the large corpus of  workflow tools we\'ve created.&nbsp; We\'ve been looking at PREMIS as a  container for exposing these records to the outside world (where  appropriate - like to an auditor perhaps), and for preserving them.&nbsp; I  have a personal interest in PREMIS and took a shot at creating PREMIS  XML for our ingest records.&nbsp; I\'d be interested in comparing notes with  others who have been working on mapping their internal ingest records to  a schema like PREMIS.\"</p>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(261,34,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Documentation identifying each class of AIP and describing how each is   implemented within the repository. Implementations may, for example,   involve some combination of files, databases, and/or documents.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.1</strong> Repository has an identifiable, written definition for each AIP or class of information preserved by the repository</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/10/trac-b21-aips.html [BB10/15/2010]:</p><p>\"Does <em>anyone </em>have written definitions for their AIPs?</p><p>I found a <a href=\"http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CD0QFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.loc.gov%2Frr%2Fmopic%2Favprot%2FAIP-Study_v19.pdf&amp;rct=j&amp;q=archival%20information%20package%20definition&amp;ei=-Ly1TLmlC4KClAf2vtXuBQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNH6QZbl9sXTyo9tvI5bc6RrAPP__A&amp;sig2=Tjbkb96u9R1Yt4g6HxbvZg&amp;cad=rja\">preliminary design document</a> &nbsp; at the Library of Congress via a Google search that had a very long,  very complete description of a proposed AIP for image-type content.&nbsp; But  in general it seems hard to find real world examples of AIPs that are  in use at working archives.&nbsp; Perhaps they are out there, but published  in such a way that makes it difficult to discover them?<br /><br />Here is  my strawman stab at defining an AIP for the bulk of ICPSR\'s content:&nbsp;  social science research data and documentation.&nbsp; This is very much a  work-in-progress and should not be read as any sort of official  document.&nbsp; Here goes:<br /><br /><em><strong>Definition of an Archival Information Package (AIP) for a Social Science Study</strong></em><br /><br />We define an AIP for a <strong>social science study</strong> as a list of files where each file has supporting representation information in the form of:</p><ul><li>a <strong>role </strong>(data, codebook, survey instrument, etc)</li><li>a <strong>format </strong>(we use MIME type)</li></ul><p>and has the following Preservation Description Information:</p><ul><li><strong>Provenance</strong>.&nbsp;  We link processed studies to initial deposits at aggregation-level, and  we also collect processing history in our internal Study Tracking  System which records who performed actions on the content, and major  milestones in its lifecycle at ICPSR.</li><li><strong>Context</strong>.&nbsp; We store  related content together in the filesystem, and a good deal of the  context embedded in both the name of each file and in a relational  database.&nbsp; While not in production, we are evaluating the use of RDF/XML  as a method for recording and exposing contextual information.</li><li><strong>Reference</strong>.&nbsp; Each file has a unique ID.</li><li><strong>Fixity</strong>.&nbsp; We use an MD5 hash at file-level to capture and check integrity.</li></ul><p>So  there\'s the strawman.&nbsp; To help guide my description of the PDI, I used  these definitions from the Open Archival Information System (OAIS)  specification:</p><blockquote><em>Provenance describes the source of the  Content Information, who has had custody of it since its origination,  and its history (including processing history).<br />Context describes how  the Content Information relates to other information outside the  Information Package. For example, it would describe why the Content  Information was produced, and it may include a description of how it  relates to another Content Information object that is available.<br />Reference  provides one or more identifiers, or systems of identifiers, by which  the Content Information may be uniquely identified. Examples include an  ISBN number for a book, or a set of attributes that distinguish one  instance of Content Information from&nbsp; another.<br />Fixity provides a  wrapper, or protective shield, that protects the Content Information  from undocumented alteration. For example, it may involve a check sum  over the Content Information of a digital Information Package</em>\"<br /></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(262,43,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Retention of individuals with the discipline expertise; periodic  assembly of designated or outside community members to evaluate and  identify additional required metadata.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.10</strong> Repository has a documented process for testing  understandability of the information content and bringing the  information content up to the agreed level of understandability.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR data processors and managers have domain expertise that  enables them to determine whether content is understandable and whether  data will be able to be effectively analyzed given the information  provided. Similarly, ICPSR employs graduate students with domain  expertise to create content for undergraduate instruction.  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR data processors have the  responsibility to determine whether data are usable and understandable  and may be released with the assumption that they can be used  effectively.&nbsp;Processors may need to contact principal investigators for  more information or supplement existing documentation in other ways. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/archiving.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/archiving.jsp</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>The  Data Documentation Initiative (DDI) is the metadata standard used at  ICPSR. It is intended to reflect best practice for documenting&nbsp;social  science research data and to represent the views of the community. DDI  is continually updated to capture new documentation needs. <a href=\"http://www.ddialliance.org/\">http://www.ddialliance.org</a> [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>Is there a need to track explicitly the processor\'s decision on  usability and actions taken to enhance it? Or iis this already done?  [Dissemination Committee]</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(263,44,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Description of the procedure that verifies completeness and correctness; logs of the procedure.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.11</strong> Repository verifies each AIP for completeness and correctness at the point it is generated.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(264,45,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Documentation provided for B2.1 through B2.6; documented agreements  negotiated between the producer and the repository (see B 1.1-B1.9);  logs of material received and associated action (receipt, action, etc.)  dates; logs of periodic checks.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.12</strong> Repository provides an independent mechanism for audit of the integrity of the repository collection/content.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(265,46,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Written documentation of decisions and/or action taken; preservation  metadata logged, stored, and linked to pertinent digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.13</strong> Repository has contemporaneous records of actions and  administration processes that are relevant to preservation (AIP  creation).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(266,35,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Documentation that relates the AIP component\'s contents to the related  preservation needs of the repository, with enough detail for the  repository\'s providers and consumers to be confident that the  significant properties of AIPs will be preserved.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.2</strong> Repository has a definition of each AIP (or class) that is adequate to fit long-term preservation needs.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/10/trac-b22-are-our-aips-adequate-to-job.html [BB 10/22/2010]:</p><p>\"This  item is somewhat difficult to discuss without a crisp set of  definitions for AIPs.&nbsp; However, given the longevity of ICPSR as a  digital repository, and given the track record (nearly fifty years) of  preserving and delivering content, the empirical evidence would seem to  indicate that the models and containers we are using for our content are  a good fit for our long-term preservation needs.<br /><br />In some ways  ICPSR has a relatively easy task here since our content is pretty  homogeneous (survey data and documentation) and we are able to normalize  it into very durable formats like plain text and TIFF.&nbsp; And because our  content is all \"born digital\" and delivered digitally, there\'s fewer  opportunities for things to go really awry.<br /><br />We also create a  great deal of descriptive metadata that we bundle with out content, and  our content is highly curated compared to, say, an enormous stream of  data coming from highway sensors or satellites.&nbsp; In addition to making  items easier to find and to use, it may also help keep them more durable  as a side-effect.<br /><br />As part of an NSF Interop/EAGER grant we\'re  defining Fedora Objects for our most common content types, and for each  object, we are also working through the specifications of the AIP.&nbsp; My  sense is that this will help us formalize some of our current practices,  and will help illuminate any gaps where we should be collecting and  saving metadata, but aren\'t today.&nbsp; And that will help further inform  the response to this TRAC item.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(267,36,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Process description documents; documentation of SIP relationship to AIP;  clear documentation of how AIPs are derived from SIPs; documentation of  standard/process against which normalization occurs; documentation of  normalization outcome and how outcome is different from SIP.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.3</strong> Repository has a description of how AIPs are constructed from SIPs.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/10/trac-b23-sips-to-aips.html [BB 10/29/2010]:</p><p>\"<em>This  particular area is under active discussion at ICPSR.&nbsp; The commentary  below describes current processes in place at ICPSR, but these processes  are likely to change in the future.</em><br /><br />Content enters archival storage at two different points in the lifecycle of a \"data processing project\" at ICPSR.<br /><br />When  a Deposit is signed, its payload of content (its files) enter archival  storage for bit-level preservation.&nbsp; The system generates a unique ID  for each deposited file and also keeps track of each file\'s MIME type,  digital signature (via MD5 hash), original name (but sanitized to avoid  SQL injection attacks and other like problems), and the date it was  received.<br /><br />A cognizant archive manager assigns each new deposit to  a data manager.&nbsp; In the most easy, most trivial case, a data manager  may package the submission for long-term preservation and release on the  ICPSR web site with little added work.&nbsp; The data manager packages the  content into an ICPSR \"study\" object, collaborates with others at ICPSR  to author descriptive and preservation metadata, and performs a series  of quality control checks, some of which are automated.&nbsp; Workflow tools  record major milestones in the life of the project, and the data manager  creates an explicit linkage between deposit and study for future  reference.&nbsp; And the system also assigns a unique ID to each of these  \"processed\" files, and captures metadata like digital signature, MIME  type, etc.<br /><br />Thus, at the aggregate level, ICPSR collects strong  documentation mapping submission objects to archival objects, but the  documentation is much weaker, and often absent, at the more detailed  level of files.&nbsp; For example, there is no explicit mapping between  deposit file X and study file Y.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(268,37,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>System processing files; disposal records; donor or depositor  agreements/deeds of gift; provenance tracking system; system log files.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.4</strong> Repository can demonstrate that all submitted objects  (i.e., SIPs) are either accepted as whole or part of an eventual  archival object (i.e., AIP), or otherwise disposed of in a recorded  fashion.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/11/trac-b24-sips-need-to-become-aips.html [BB 11/8/1020]:</p><p>\"This  TRAC requirement moves us away from the technology area and into  business processes in other parts of ICPSR.&nbsp; As such my critique comes  more from a perspective of an informed outsider rather than the  responsible party.<br /><br />My sense is that ICPSR has a good review  process in place such that deposits are tracked on a regular basis by  our acquisitions staff.&nbsp; If a deposit becomes stuck - which can happen  for all sorts of different reasons, only some of which are under the  control of ICPSR - the acquisitions team makes sure that it does not  fall off the radar screen.<br /><br />That said, it is certainly possible  for ICPSR to receive an unsolicited deposit from a researcher, find some  problems with the data or the documentation, and then run into barriers  when working with the researcher to resolve the issues.&nbsp; In this case a  deposit can move very slowly through ICPSR\'s machinery, and may take  many years to emerge.&nbsp; However, even in an uncommon case such as this,  we will have records that track and document the barriers so that there  is formal institutional memory about the deposit.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(269,38,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Documentation describing naming convention and physical evidence of its application (e.g., logs).</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.5</strong> Repository has and uses a naming convention that  generates visible, persistent, unique identifiers for all archived  objects (i.e., AIPs).</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR Filenaming Conventions (Source: <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/INTRA/data/filenaming.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/INTRA/data/filenaming.html</a>) [JAL &amp; LTS, 8/4/2009] </li></ul>',4,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/11/trac-b25-aip-naming-conventions.html [BB 11/12/2010]:</p><p>\"ICPSR  generates a unique ID for each file that we receive via a deposit, and a  unique ID for each post-processed file that we create.&nbsp; Files are  stored in well-defined locations in archival storage, and between the  location and filename (which also follows a set of standard conventions  within ICPSR), one can identify considerable provenance information  which is also replicated in a database.<br /><br />Specifically, each file  that has been deposited at ICPSR - if retained for preservation - has a  unique ID stored in a database, and has a unique location in archival  storage:&nbsp; deposits/depositID/originalFilenameSanitized.&nbsp; The root of the  location varies depending upon the physical location of the copy in  archival storage.&nbsp; For example, a copy stored locally at ICPSR may have a  URI root of file://nas.icpsr.umich.edu/archival-storage while a copy  stored in an off-site archival location will have a different URI root.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(270,39,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Workflow documents and evidence of traceability (e.g., SIP identifier embedded in AIP, mapping table of SIP IDs to AIPs).</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.6</strong> If unique identifiers are associated with SIPs before  ingest, the repository preserves the identifiers in a way that maintains  a persistent association with the resultant archived object (e.g.,  AIP).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/11/trac-b26-matching-unique-sip-ids-to-aip.html [BB 11/19/2010]:</p><p>\"My sense is that ICPSR is in pretty good shape on this requirement.&nbsp; Here is a stab at the documentation.<br /><br />ICPSR  collects the original file name (sanitized to avoid problems via SQL  injection and other attacks) for each item at the time of deposit.&nbsp; Each  item also receives a unique ID in our deposit tracking system.&nbsp; And the  deposit event itself also receives a unique ID which is also exposed to  the depositor. <br /><br />During the data curation process an ICPSR data  manager will mint a new container-level object for access purposes  (i.e., a study), and will fill that container with materials derived  from the deposit.&nbsp; This activity can run the gamut from a one-to-one  mapping between deposited files and released files to something far more  complex.&nbsp; In any event ICPSR records and preserves the mapping between  the aggregate-level objects, deposits and studies.&nbsp; ICPSR also has plans  to record and preserve the mapping at the more fine-grained level of  each file.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(271,40,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Subscription or access to such registries; association of unique identifiers to format registries with digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.7</strong> Repository demonstrates that it has access to necessary  tools and resources to establish authoritative semantic or technical  context of the digital objects it contains (i.e., access to appropriate  international Representation Information and format registries).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/11/trac-b27-format-registries.html [BB 11/24/2010]:</p><p>\"The  volume of content entering ICPSR is relatively low, perhaps 100  submissions per month.&nbsp; In some extreme cases, such as with our  Publication Related Archive, ICPSR staff spend relatively little time  reviewing and normalizing content, and it is released \"as is\" on the web  site, and it gets the most modest level of digital preservation  (bit-level only, unless the content happens to be something more  durable, such as plain text).&nbsp; However, in most cases, someone at ICPSR  is opening each file, reading and reviewing documentation, scrubbing  data for disclosure risk, recoding, etc, etc.&nbsp; It is a very hands-on  process.<br /><br />Because of the low volumes and high touches, automated  format detection is not at all essential, at least for the current  business model.&nbsp; Nonetheless we do use automated format detection for  both the files that we receive via our deposit system, and for the  derivative files we produce internally.&nbsp; And our tool for doing this is  the venerable UNIX command-line utility file.<br /><br />Why?<br /><br />The  content that we tend to receive is a mix of documentation and data.&nbsp; The  documentation is often in PDF format, but sometimes arrives in common  word processor formats like DOC and DOCS, and sometimes less common word  processor formats.&nbsp; The data is often in a format produced by common  statistical packages such as SAS, SPSS, and Stata.&nbsp; And we also get a  nice mix of other file formats from a wide variety of business  applications like Access, Excel, PowerPoint, and more.<br /><br />We have  found the vanilla file that ships with Red Hat Linux to be pretty good  at most of the formats that show up on our doorstep.&nbsp; We\'ve extended the  magic database that file consults so that it does a better job  understanding a more broad selection of stat package formats.&nbsp; (file  does OK, but not great in this area.)&nbsp; We also have extended the magic  database and wrapped file in a helper tool&nbsp; -- we call the final product  ifile, for improved file -- so that it does a better job identifying  the newer Microsoft Office file formats like DOCX, XLSX, PPTX, and so  on.<br /><br />I would love to be able to use an \"off the shelf\" tool like  jhove or droid to identify file formats, relying upon a global registry  for formats.&nbsp; There isn\'t much glamor in hacking the magic database.<br /><br />However,  my experience thus far with jhove, jhove2, and droid is that they just  don\'t beat ifile (or even file) for the particular mix of content we  tend to get.&nbsp; Those packages are much more heavy-weight, and while they  do a fabulous job on some formats (like PDF), they perform poorly or not  at all with many of the formats we see on a regular basis.<br /><br />As a  test I took a week or two of the files most recently deposited at ICPSR,  and I had file, ifile, and droid have a go at identifying them.&nbsp; I  originally had jhove2 in the mix as well, but I could not get it to run  reliably.&nbsp; (And my sense is that it may be using the same data source as  droid for file identification anyway.)&nbsp; Of the 249 files I examined,  ifile got \'em all right, file misreported on 48 of them, and droid  misreported 104 files.&nbsp; And the number for droid gets worse if I ding it  for reporting a file containing an email as text/plain rather than  text/rfc822.<br /><br />So in the end we\'re using our souped-up version of  file for file format identification, and we\'re using IANA MIME types as  our primary identifier for file format.&nbsp; We also capture the more  verbose human-readable output from our own ifile as well since it can be  handy to have \"SPSS System File MS Windows Release 10.0.5\" rather than  just application/x-spss.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(272,41,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Viewable records in local format registry (with persistent links to  digital objects); local metadata registry(ies); database records that  include Representation Information and a persistent link to relevant  digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.8</strong> Repository records/registers Representation Information (including formats) ingested.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/12/trac-b28-capturing-representation.html [BB 12/3/2010]:</p><p>\"As  noted in last week\'s post, we capture representation information in   both IANA MIME type form and also in a more human-readable form. We are   also looking at adding an additional piece of representation  information  to the metadata that surrounds the files deposited at  ICPSR:&nbsp; file type  or file role.<br /> <br /> In brief, the idea is to  capture the high-level concept behind the role  the file plays in  research.&nbsp; For example, it may be nice to know that a  given file is an  Excel workbook, but it is also important to know  whether the file  contains data, documentation, a database of sorts, or  some combination  of things.&nbsp; An Excel file that contains nothing but  columns of numbers  and text might be normalized quite easily into a more  durable format.&nbsp;  An Excel file that contains nothing but text and  images and  descriptions of a data file might be converted to PDF/A or  TIFF or some  other format.<br /> <br /> This idea has been used with the derived content  that ICPSR produces for  a very long time, but ICPSR is just now  exploring the required changes  in business process to do this for  deposited files as well.&nbsp; More as  this story develops....\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(273,42,'B. Digital Object Management','B2. Ingest: Creation of the Archivable Package','<p>Viewable records in local format registry (with persistent links to  digital objects); local metadata registry(ies); database records that  include Representation Information and a persistent link to relevant  digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B2.9</strong> Repository acquires preservation metadata (i.e., PDI) for its associated Content Information.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2011/01/trac-b29-collecting-preservation.html [BB 1/14/2011]:</p><p>\"My  sense is that ICPSR is in pretty good shape on this item.&nbsp; We have an  entire database schema devotes to our objects in Archival Storage, and  we collect (and store) a great deal of information about content  starting when a depositor first gives it to us (e.g., checksum via md5,  identity of depositor, file format), and then extending throughout the  ingest process.&nbsp; This content is readily available to internal staff  through a no-frills, but extremely useful database browser that someone  on my team built several years ago.<br /><br />One thing that we don\'t do  today is annotate original content at the file level with information  about its role; I think this would fall within the scope of Context  Information above.&nbsp; For instance, if someone deposits a file called  MySurvey.xls, we do not add a comment that says, \"Oh, this is survey  data.\"&nbsp; I\'ve been participating in meetings where this particular issue  is getting some discussion, and my expectation is that sometime this  year we (in the IT shop) will need to build some simple extensions to  existing systems to implement features like this.<br /><br />One bit of  Context Information that we do collect (at the end of ingest) is a  mapping at the aggregate level between original submissions to ICPSR  (i.e., deposits) and the content we ingest and deliver (i.e.,  studies).\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(274,47,'B. Digital Object Management','B3. Preservation Planning','<p>Documentation identifying each preservation issue and the strategy for dealing with that issue.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B3.1</strong> Repository has documented preservation strategies.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(275,48,'B. Digital Object Management','B3. Preservation Planning','<p>Subscription to a format registry service; subscription to a technology  watch service; percentage of at least one staff member dedicated to  monitoring technological obsolescence issues.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><strong>B3.2</strong> Repository has mechanisms in place for monitoring and  notification when Representation Information (including formats)  approaches obsolescence or is no longer viable.</p>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(276,49,'B. Digital Object Management','B3. Preservation Planning','<p>Preservation planning policies tied to formal or information technology  watch(es); preservation planning or processes that are timed to shorter  intervals (e.g., not more than five years); proof of frequent  preservation planning/policy updates.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><strong>B3.3</strong> Repository has mechanisms to change its preservation plans as a result of its monitoring activities.</p>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(277,50,'B. Digital Object Management','B3. Preservation Planning','<p>Collection of appropriate preservation metadata; proof of usability of  randomly selected digital objects held within the system; demonstrable  track record for retaining usable digital objects over time.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><strong>B3.4</strong> Repository can provide evidence of the effectiveness of its preservation planning.</p>','<p>Downloads</p>',NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(278,52,'B. Digital Object Management','B4. Archival Storage &amp; Preservation/Maintenance of AIPs','<p>Documentation of strategies and their appropriateness to repository  objects; evidence of application (e.g., in preservation metadata); see  B3.3.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><strong>B4.1</strong> Repository employs documented preservation strategies.</p>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(279,54,'B. Digital Object Management','B4. Archival Storage &amp; Preservation/Maintenance of AIPs','<p>Institutional technology and standards watch; demonstration of objects  on which a preservation strategy has been performed; demonstration of  appropriate preservation metadata for digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B4.2</strong> Repository implements/responds to strategies for archival object (i.e., AIP) storage and migration.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(280,56,'B. Digital Object Management','B4. Archival Storage &amp; Preservation/Maintenance of AIPs','<p>Policy documents specifying treatment of AIPs and whether they may ever  be deleted; ability to demonstrate the chain of AIPs for any particular  digital object or group of objects ingested; workflow procedure  documentation.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B4.3</strong> Repository preserves the Content Information of archival objects (i.e., AIPs).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(281,58,'B. Digital Object Management','B4. Archival Storage &amp; Preservation/Maintenance of AIPs','<p>Logs of fixity checks (e.g., checksums); documentation of how AIPs and Fixity information are kept separate.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B4.4</strong> Repository actively monitors integrity of archival objects (i.e., AIPs).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(282,60,'B. Digital Object Management','B4. Archival Storage &amp; Preservation/Maintenance of AIPs','<p>Written documentation of decisions and/or action taken; preservation  metadata logged, stored, and linked to pertinent digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B4.5</strong> Repository has contemporaneous records of actions and  administration processes that are relevant to preservation (Archival  Storage).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(283,62,'B. Digital Object Management','B5. Information Management','<p>Descriptive metadata.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B5.1</strong> Repository articulates minimum metadata requirements to  enable the designated community(ies) to discover and identify material  of interest.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(284,65,'B. Digital Object Management','B5. Information Management','<p>Descriptive metadata; persistent identifier/locator associated with AIP;  system documentation and technical architecture; depositor agreements;  metadata policy documentation, incorporating details of metadata  requirements and a statement describing where responsibility for its  procurement falls; process workflow documentation.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B5.2</strong> Repository captures or creates minimum descriptive  metadata and ensures that it is associated with the archived object  (i.e., AIP).</h3>','<ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: \'Verdana\',\'sans-serif\';\">ICPSR states that a study description will be created (in the Deposit Data &amp; Findings section on the ICPSR website <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit/index.jsp</a>) but specifics are not conveyed.<span>&nbsp; </span>Internal  documents from the intranet (Data pipeline step 10) detail which fields  are necessary for the different levels of metadata.<span>&nbsp; </span>[LQ 10/10]</span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: \'Verdana\',\'sans-serif\';\">ICPSR  discloses standards followed and describes types of metadata and  formats (in the Digital Curation section of the ICPSR website <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/metadata.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/metadata.jsp</a> ). [LQ 10/10]</span></li></ul> <ul><li><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: \'Verdana\',\'sans-serif\';\">A persistent URL for studies is used as an identifier/locater.<span>&nbsp; </span>However,<span>&nbsp; </span></span><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: \'Verdana\',\'sans-serif\';\">ICPSR is really still a \"file-level\" repository vs an AIP-level repository in terms of linking metadata to objects.&nbsp; Archival<span>&nbsp; </span>metadata (including the unique file ID) resides in an Oracle table called DLIBCLEAN.FILES.&nbsp;<span>&nbsp; </span>The Schema Browser webapp (<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DBInfo/\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DBInfo/</a>) documents the fields. <span>[LQ 10/10]</span></span></li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: \'Verdana\',\'sans-serif\';\">While ICPSR encourages data producers to provide metadata for their studies, it does not require it.<span>&nbsp; </span>Should<span>&nbsp; </span>producer choose to include such metadata, ICPSR provides multiple avenues for assistance through the website. [LQ 10/10]</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 9pt; font-family: \'Verdana\',\'sans-serif\';\">Some   metadata is captured automatically, such as file type and data file   variables and cases and is communicated to the depositor.<span>&nbsp; </span>[LQ 10/10]</span></p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(285,67,'B. Digital Object Management','B5. Information Management','<p>Descriptive metadata; persistent identifier/locator associated with AIP;  documented relationship between AIP and metadata; system documentation  and technical architecture; process workflow documentation.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B5.3</strong> Repository can demonstrate that referential integrity is  created between all archived objects (i.e., AIPs) and associated  descriptive information.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(286,71,'B. Digital Object Management','B5. Information Management','<p>Log detailing ongoing monitoring/checking of referential integrity,  especially following repair/modification of AIP; legacy descriptive  metadata; persistence of identifier/locator; documented relationship  between AIP and metadata; system documentation and technical  architecture; process workflow documentation.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B5.4</strong> Repository can demonstrate that referential integrity is  maintained between all archived objects (i.e., AIPs) and associated  descriptive information.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(287,75,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>Public versions of access policies; delivery policies; fee policies.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.1</strong> Repository documents and communicates to its designated community(ies) what access and delivery options are available.</h3>','<ul><li>The words \"Access Notes\" are clearly marked in red text and are found on every study home page. Examples are: <br /><ul><li>\"One or more files in this study are restricted; consult the <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/22580/detail\">detailed metadata page</a> to learn more.\" [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>\"This data is available only to users at ICPSR member institutions. Because you are not <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/mydata?path=ICPSR&amp;request_uri=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.icpsr.umich.edu%2Ficpsrweb%2FICPSR%2Fstudies%2F8079\">logged in</a> , we cannot verify that you will be able to download the data.\"[Dissemination Committee]</li></ul></li><li>There  are ICPSR web pages on accessing restricted data, including information  about restricted use data and how to apply for it.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>There are ICPSR web pages on data  format types that are available. There is a link to this page on every  study\'s download page, as well.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/help/more-info.jsp  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>The Download Select Files page for a  study has a detailed table of download options that make it easy to  identify and download only the files of interest.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/6849/system&nbsp;  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>The Download Select Files page also  has the word \"Restricted\"in red text at the top with a description to  alert data users that parts of the study can only be accessed through a  restricted use agreement.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/27026?archive=ICPSR&amp;q=add+health  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>The Download Select Files page has a  column on the right with Notes about more access information, including  the link to the ICPSR data format types page, a notice that the  documentation for the study will come with a data file download, notice  that the file size listed in the table is of the uncompressed files, and  information about what \"other files\" includes.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/6849/system  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>The Browse Documentation page for a  study will have the Restricted-Use agreement available for download.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/20862/documentation  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>There are ICPSR web pages on  Membership, including information on what it means to be a member, a  list of current members, how to become a member, and how to access date  if you are not a member.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/membership/index.jsp  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>There is a list of FAQs that are  categorized under \"Access\" on the Help web pages.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/icpsr/access&nbsp;  [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR has an Access Policy that is  publicly available.  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp  [Dissemination Committee] </li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(288,77,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>System design documents; work instructions (if DIPs involve manual  processing); process walkthroughs; production of a sample authenticated  copy; documentation of community requirements for authentication.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><strong>B6.10</strong> Repository enables the dissemination of authentic copies of the original or objects traceable to originals.</p>','<ul><li>Working with Data/The ICPSR Pipeline Process  (Source:https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1856)  [MIWS, Dissemination 4/1/2010]</li><li>Why Deposit Data Long-Term  Preservation. ICPSR ensures long-term data availability. ICPSR Data  Deposit Data &amp; Findings. (Source:  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit) [MIWS,  Dissemination 4/1/2010]</li><li>Technological and Procedural  Suitability: The majority of digital content in the collectionsat ICPSR  currently consists of social science research data, requisite  documentation to use and understand the data, and associated files. Upon  receipt of a deposit, ICPSR processes the digital content to ensure  that confidential information has not been included in the data;  corrects errors; fills gaps in the documentation; and produces  distribution versions of the data. Technicians digitize documentation  that is received only in hard copy format. ICPSR archives the original  digital content received, the normalized versions of processed data, and  superseded versions of data that have been distributed. The archived  files will enable ICPSR to retain the ability to regenerate distribution  formats over time. For files submitted on physical storage media, ICPSR  makes archival copies but does not preserve the original transmission  media. In terms of documentation, ICPSR has been an active participant  in the development of and is an adherent to the Data Documentation  Initiative (DDI) standard. Digital Preservation Policies and Planning at  ICPSR. (Source:  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/dpp-framework.jsp)  [MIWS, Dissemination 4/1/2010]</li><li>The Archival Storage function  provides onsite and offsite redundancy through online copies (and a tape  copy as extra backup) of ICPSR\'s digital content, both the archival  copies and the access copies. ICPSR preserves the ability to regenerate  the Dissemination Information Package (DIP); we do not preserve the  software-dependent files (e.g., SAS, SPSS, Stata) that are distributed.  Archival storage contributes to ensuring business continuity for ICPSR  and is a component of the disaster planning at ICPSR. Digital  Preservation Policies (Source:  http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/glossary.jsp?word=Archival+Storage)  [MIWS, Dissemination 4/1/2010] Study Tracking Database-Study Tracking  System. (Source: http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/INTRA/sts) [MI WS,  Dissemination 4/1/2010]</li><li>ICPSR data processors archive Processing History files, which are syntax files that indicate how the data were transformed.&nbsp; </li></ul>',2,'Action Item(s)','<p>Need for more explicit statement of how data and documentation are transformed, perhaps using a controlled vocabulary.</p>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(289,78,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>Access policies; use statements.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.2</strong> Repository has implemented a policy for recording all  access actions (includes requests, orders etc.) that meet the  requirements of the repository and information producers/depositors.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR is able to obtain information about users via such things  as Google analytics and web server statistics.&nbsp; This includes such  information as IP addresses, dates of access, and which files were  reviewed by users.&nbsp; <a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/node/1194\">https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/node/1194</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>For  restricted data access, users must complete a restricted data request  form which includes information regarding the user. All information on  restricted data access is kept in a database.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/agreement.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/agreement.jsp</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>Data depositors complete a data deposit form which includes information regarding the user. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/cgi-bin/bob/ddf</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li><li>ICPSR MyData accounts include user information.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0044\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0044</a> [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>User Support is able to capture user information via Footprints.&nbsp; [Dissemination Committee]</li><li>Detailed  utilization reports are generated to understand data access and usage  by different categories of membership. Usage statistics are publicly  available. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/files/ICPSR/or/annualreport/\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/files/ICPSR/or/annualreport/</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li></ul>',4,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(290,81,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>Access policies; logs of user access and user denials; access system  mechanisms that prevent unauthorized actions (such as save, print,  etc.); user compliance agreements.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.3</strong> Repository ensures that agreements applicable to access conditions are adhered to.</h3>','<ul><li>Data Deposit Form/auxiliary agreements executed by PI and ICPSR detail access conditions. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/deposit/index.jsp</a></li></ul><ul><li>For data downloads: users must establish an ICPSR MyData account, which carries a user profile and indicates identity.&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0044\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0044</a></li></ul><ul><li>For all downloads: users must agree (by clicking on button) to terms of use before access to download screen. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0258\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/support/faqs/0258</a></li></ul><ul><li>For  nonmembers attempting to download members-only data: a message  indicating authorization is required appears.&nbsp;&nbsp; Only documentation files  download. </li></ul><ul><li>Information on nonmember access to members-only data is on web site (Membership section and in an FAQ). <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/membership/nonmember.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/membership/nonmember.jsp</a></li></ul><ul><li>For  members downloading members-only data: their computer IP address must  be in IP range provided to ICPSR or user login must be associated with  member school via previous login from IP range. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp</a>;</li></ul><ul><li>For  restricted data: presence of restricted data for a study is noted on  study page with more details provided in Access section of metadata.&nbsp;  Link to application information/forms requiring proof of identity and  authorization appears in metadata. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/27026?archive=ICPSR&amp;q=add+health\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/27026?archive=ICPSR&amp;q=add+health</a></li></ul><ul><li>Web site has page on restricted data and application process. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp</a></li></ul><ul><li>Restricted data use applications/agreements reviewed and approved/rejected by appropriate archive. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp</a></li></ul><ul><li>Original  restricted data use agreements maintained in locked file cabinets and  restricted data user information maintained in access database. </li></ul><ul><li>Internal  prodecures manual for processing and tracking approved restricted data  use requests, including steps to take when agreements expire. </li></ul><ul><li>Access  questions from users captured and responded to in an organization-wide  tracking system by user support and individual archives.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/shared/ICPSR/help/index\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/shared/ICPSR/help/index</a></li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR has an Access Policy that describes access conditions for all categories of users and for all types of resources held. <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp</a></li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(291,83,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>Access validation mechanisms within system; documentation of authentication and validation procedures.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.4</strong> Repository has documented and implemented access  policies (authorization rules, authentication requirements) consistent  with deposit agreements for stored objects.</h3>','<ul><li>The ICPSR Access Policy provides detail on authentication and  authorization rules for ICPSR data resources according to user types  (member/nonmember) as well as access mechanisms.&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/curation/preservation/policies/access-policy-framework.jsp</a> [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul><ul><li>ICPSR\'s  registration system, MyData, provides a degree of authentication and  also forms the basis for authorization for specific data resources  through its link to IP address. <a href=\"http://icpsr-support.blogspot.com/2009/05/what-is-mydata.html\">http://icpsr-support.blogspot.com/2009/05/what-is-mydata.html</a>. [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul><ul><li>The ICPSR profile tied to MyData accounts provides a basic set of credentials (first three required):</li></ul><blockquote>Email address <br />MyData password (you create this) <br />Name <br />Academic status (student, faculty, staff, etc.) <br />Department, discipline, or academic unit <br />Which statistical package you prefer <br />Whether  or not we can share your name, email address, and download information  with your institution\'s appointed ICPSR representative [Dissemination  Committee]</blockquote><ul><li>ICPSR requires the completion of a  restricted-use contract in order to access data that is classified as  restricted either as a result of a deposit agreement or as a result of a  determination by ICPSR staff that the content is sensitive and access  must be controlled. <a href=\"http://matvey.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp\">http://matvey.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp</a>&nbsp;[Dissemination Committee]</li></ul><ul><li>Repository staff are permitted to access only those files that they own. [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>Do we need to explicitly tie the deposit agreement with the AIP or is this already done? [Dissemination Committee]</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(292,84,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>Logs and audit trails of access requests; information about user  capabilities (authentication matrices); explicit tests of some types of  access.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.5</strong> Repository access management system fully implements access policy.</h3>','<ul><li>ICPSR\'s Access Policy spells out the authorization rules for the various types of digital resources that ICPSR disseminates (<a href=\"http://matvey.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp\">http://matvey.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp</a>):</li></ul><blockquote><span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica; font-size: x-small;\">Authorized Users </span><p><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: helvetica; font-size: x-small;\">Data  users at ICPSR member institutions in good standing may access all of  ICPSR\'s online data holdings, including those data curated through  membership revenues, after logging in with a MyData account and agreeing  to Terms of Use. Membership authorization is done by IP range. </span></p></span></span></span></blockquote><blockquote><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: helvetica; font-size: x-small;\">Other  users may access data curated through grant and contract funding, which  are available free of charge to anyone, after logging in with a MyData  account and agreeing to Terms of Use. Individuals at nonmember  institutions may access members-only data for a fee.</span></blockquote><ul><li><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: helvetica; font-size: x-small;\">To  obtain authorization to use restricted data, prospective data users  must complete restricted-use data agreements, which are legal contracts  signed by both the user\'s institution and ICPSR. These agreements  describe critical data protection practices as well as procedures for  destroying the data after the access period expires.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://matvey.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp\">http://matvey.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/access/restricted/index.jsp</a> <span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana;\">[Dissemination Committee]</span></span></li></ul><ul><li>For  nonmembers attempting to download members-only data: a message  indicating authorization is required appears.&nbsp;&nbsp; Only documentation files  download. [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul><ul><li>For users attempting to  download restricted data, a message appears saying that they are not  authorized to receive the data. [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul><ul><li>All access requests are logged. [Dissemination Committee]</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>Language on Access Policy Webpage has changed [EB 1/14/2011]</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(293,85,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>Access logs; capability of system to use automated analysis/monitoring  tools and generate problem/error messages; notes of reviews undertaken  or action taken as result of reviews.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.6</strong> Repository logs all access management failures, and staff review inappropriate access denial incidents.</h3>','<ul><li>MyData authentication failures are currently logged to an error  log file with an indication of whether the failure was due to a bad  password or a non-existent user name (email address.)&nbsp; The username  (email address) used in the attempted authentication is also logged.&nbsp;  While this error log file is periodically reviewed by CNS development  staff, the authentication failures are not checked for validity.</li><li>An alert is sent out when a restricted-use file is downloaded without authorization.</li></ul>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(294,82,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>System design documents; work instructions (if DIPs involve manual  processing); process walkthroughs; logs of orders and DIP production;  test accesses to verify delivery of appropriate digital objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.7</strong> Repository can demonstrate that the process that  generates the requested digital object(s) (i.e., DIP) is completed in  relation to the request.</h3>','<p>Currently, a zip package is delivered to the user after he/she makes a  request. The zip file lists all filesÂ&nbsp;requested, identified by their  file names that have extensions descriptive of the format.  [Dissemination Committee]</p><p>When attempting to download restricted  data but not authorized to receive it, the user gets all files except  the restricted ones and gets a message that he or she must complete a  restricted use data agreement. [Dissemination Committee]</p><p>ICPSR has  a potential project to create customized manifests that list the actual  files delivered to the user. Currently, the manifest is a list of all  files associated with a study. [Dissemination Committee]</p><p>ICPSR has a project to define the elements of a DIP as well as a SIP and AIP. [Dissemination Committee]</p>',2,'Action Item(s)','<p>Need to develop a download-specific file manifest</p><p>Need to identify elements of SIPs, AIPs, and DIPs if not already done.</p>',NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,1,NULL),(295,80,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p><em>Evidence:</em> System design documents; work instructions (if DIPs involve manual  processing); process walkthroughs; logs of orders and DIP production.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.8 </strong>Repository can demonstrate that the process that  generates the requested digital object(s) (i.e., DIP) is correct in  relation to the request.</h3>','<p>ICPSR currently distributes files already in existence rather than  creating or generating them on the fly, and the components of the de  facto DIP have already been specified. ICPSR has a project to define the  elements of a DIP as well as a SIP and AIP. [Dissemination Committee]</p>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(296,79,'B. Digital Object Management','B6. Access Management','<p>System design documents; work instructions (if DIPs involve manual  processing); process walkthroughs; logs of orders and DIP production.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>B6.9</strong> Repository demonstrates that all access requests result in a response of acceptance or rejection.</h3>','<p>Nonmembers trying to access members-only data get this message: <span style=\"font-size: 14pt; font-family: \'Calibri\',\'sans-serif\';\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">“These  data are available only to users at ICPSR member institutions. Because  you are not &nbsp;*logged in*, we cannot verify that you will be able to  download the data.”<br /><br /></span></span></span>Member trying to download data from off-campus with account&nbsp;not validated for off-campus access,&nbsp;or those <span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\">logged  in and&nbsp;but not a member get this message: ”These data are available  only to users at ICPSR member institutions; you are not at a member  institution. Thus you &nbsp;may only download the documentation files. If you  believe this an error, please consult our *FAQs on access*.”<br /><br /></span>Users  trying to access restricted data: Note on download page that study  contains restricted data with more details provided in metadata Access  section. Link in metadata to application information/forms.</p><p>Restricted  data: user either sent data and copy of fully-executed agreement or  informed of inadequate submission by appropriate archive. Inadequate  submission communications maintained by archive, typically in an email.</p><p>Restricted  data: when agreement expires researchers told to either request an  extension and provide evidence of local IRB approval or destroy data and  return affidavit.&nbsp; If noncompliant, researcher instructed to destroy  data per terms of agreement.</p><p>Restricted data: internal manual for processing and tracking restricted data use agreements/researchers.</p>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(297,76,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Software inventory; system documentation; support contracts; use of strongly communitysupported software (i.e., Apache).</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.1</strong> Repository functions on well-supported operating systems and other core infrastructural software.</h3>','<p>See the <a href=\"http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/09/trac-c11-well-supported-core.html\">TRAC: C1.1: Well-supported core infrastructure</a> post at the Technology at ICPSR blog for a discussion on how CNS is complying with this requirement</p>',NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/09/trac-c11-well-supported-core.html [BB 9/30/2009]:</p><p>\"At  the foundation of ICPSR\'s core technology infrastructure is Red Hat  Linux. Linux, of course, is a very widely deployed open source variant  of UNIX, and Red Hat is a world leader in supporting Linux. ICPSR had  previously used proprietary operating systems, but moved all of its  systems to Red Hat Linux in the decade.<br /><br />Moving up in the stack of  our core technology infrastructure we use several pieces of software  from the Apache Software Foundation, a very large community of  developers and users. In addition to the flagship HTTP Server, we also  use the tomcat servlet container for all of our Java-based web  applications, the Solr search engine which is built atop the Lucene Java  search technology, and the cocoon framework for rendering XML into  other formats.<br /><br />ICPSR also builds and maintains a suite of custom  software for key business processes, such as our Data Deposit Form  (ingest), our download system (access), and our data processing systems  (data management, ingest, access). While this software is necessarily  proprietary, it is written in common, modern software languages such as  Perl and Java, which have wide support in the community.<br /><br />Like  many, many enterprises, ICPSR uses Oracle as its database system. Given  the large installed base of Oracle across the world, ICPSR views this as  a well-supported platform. We believe we can continue to use Oracle as  long as the University of Michigan continues to make it freely available  to us. Further, we make use of only the most basic elements of Oracle,  and if required, it would be straight-forward, but not insignificant, to  migrate our content to any other relational database technology, such  as postgres or mysql. Our one highly customized use of Oracle, and  therefore the one that carries the most risk, is the OracleText-based  search engine for the Child Care site, is scheduled to be replaced in  early 2010.<br /><br />And finally, we are actively migrating our own  proprietary archival storage system to the Fedora system, which is  supported by the newly created DuraSpace organization. Other than  internally created systems, Fedora probably has the smallest community  of support of any of our major technology systems, but because it is  open source and gaining traction in the community, we believe its level  of support will continue to grow over time. And further, because the  underlying content resides in plain XML files, even with a sudden and  catastrophic loss of Fedora, it would still be possible to migrate  content to another system.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(298,63,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Risk register (list of all patches available and risk documentation  analysis); evidence of update processes (e.g., server update manager  daemon); documentation related to the update installations.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.10</strong> Repository has a process to react to the availability of new software security updates based on a risk-benefit assessment.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/01/trac-c110-patching-and-risk-benefit.html [BB 1/5/2010]:</p><p>\"Like  many organizations ICPSR uses an automated system for basic security  patching, both on the Windows platform and on the Linux platform. In  this context there is absolutely no risk assessment for an individual  patch; they flow from a trusted source, and are installed automatically.<br /><br />For  our most sensitive components, such as the Apache web server, Oracle,  and the kernel we run on our Linux systems, we install patches and/or  upgrade versions manually. These changes take place less often, and at a  minimum are announced well ahead of time to the entire group. For  example, a systems administrator would announce an intention to upgrade  to the newest release of the Apache web server on our staging server,  see how things work for a week, and then announce the same upgrade on  our production web server. This isn\'t captured in anything as formal as a  risk register, but there is clear and frequent communication about the  change.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(299,74,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Documentation of what is being backed up and how often; audit   log/inventory of backups; Trustworthy Repositories Audit &amp;   Certification: Criteria and Checklist validation of completed backups;   disaster recovery plan policy and documentation; firedrills testing of   backups; support contracts for hardware and software for backup   mechanisms.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.2</strong> Repository ensures that it has adequate hardware and  software support for backup functionality sufficient for the  repository\'s services and for the data held, e.g., metadata associated  with access controls, repository main content.</h3>','<ul><li>\"System backups for disaster recovery\" (Source: <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edudrupal/5\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/5</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul> <ul><li>\"Web Services Continuity at ICPSR\" (Source: <a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/sites/webservices.itcs.umich.edu.drupal.ICPSR/files/Web_services_continuity.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/sites/webservices.itcs.umich.edu.drupal.ICPSR/files/Web_services_continuity.pdf</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</li></ul>',2,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/10/trac-c12-backup-infrastructure.html [BB 10/7/2009]:</p><p>\"ICPSR  has extensive documentation and infrastructure to support its core  access functions even when a catastrophic failure disables its primary  location in Ann Arbor, Michigan. The documentation - planning documents  and instructions - reside in a Google Group, and all members of the IT  team, and two of ICPSR\'s senior staff outside of IT are members of the  group. The process has been used twice in 2009, once as a test, and once  when the Ann Arbor site suffered a power failure.<br /><br />ICPSR has a  less well documented, but fairly prosaic, backup solution in place. All  non-ephemeral content at ICPSR resides on a large Network Attached  Storage (NAS) appliance. The IT team has configured the NAS to  \"checkpoint\" each filesystem once per day, and each checkpoint is  retained for 30 days. Checkpoints provide a read-only, self-serve backup  system for those instances where a member of the staff has  inadvertently damaged or destroyed non-archival content.<br /><br />Further,  we write all filesystems to a tape library, which is located in a  different machine room than the NAS. Every two weeks tapes are removed  from the tape library, and stored in yet a different building. We retain  the last four weekly backups, and the last twelve monthly backups. The  system is exercised on an infrequent, but regular basis when we restore  files that were damaged or destroyed beyond the thirty day checkpoint  window.<br /><br />Finally, unlike \"working\" files where all copies reside  locally, and where we retain only one year of content, our archival  storage solution consists of copies in at least four locations. The  master copy (1) is on the NAS; a copy (2) is written to tape each month;  a copy (3) is synchronized daily with the San Diego Supercomputer  Center\'s storage grid; and, a copy (4) is synchronized daily with the  MATRIX Center at Michigan State University. Furthermore, archival  content collected prior to 2009 has also been copied into the  Chronopolis project storage grid, which adds two additional copies.<br /><br />One  area with room for improvement would be regular \"fire drills\" where we  would attempt to retrieve a random number of random objects from an  arbitrarily selected archival storage location.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(300,73,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>random retrieval tests; system test; location register/log of digital  objects compared to the expected number and location of copies of  particular objects.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.3</strong> Repository manages the number and location of copies of all digital objects.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/10/trac-c13-managing-all-objects.html [BB 10/14/2009]:</p><p>\"Our story here is a mixed bag of successes and barriers.<br /><br />For  the master copy of any object we can easily and quickly specify its  location. And for the second (tape) copy, we too can easily specify the  location as long as we\'re not too specific. For example, we can point to  the tape library and say, \"It\'s in there.\" And, of course, with a  little more work, we can use our tape management system to point us to  the specific tape, and the location on that tape. Maintaining this  information outside of the tape management system would be expensive,  and it\'s not clear if there would be any true benefit.<br /><br />The  location of other copies can be derived easily, but those specific  locations are not recorded in a database. For example, let\'s say that  the master copy of every original deposit we have is stored in a  filesystem hierarchy like /archival-storage/deposits/<em>deposit-id/</em>. And let\'s say that on a daily basis we synchronize that content via <em>rsync </em>to an off-site location, say, <strong>remote-location.icpsr.umich.edu:</strong>/archival-storage/deposits/<em>deposit-id/</em>. And let\'s also say that someone reviews the output of the <em>rsync </em>run on a daily basis, and also performs a random spot-check on an irregular basis.<br /><br />In  this scenario we might have a large degree of confidence that we could  find a copy of any given deposit on that off-site location. We know it\'s  there because <em>rsync </em>told us it put it there. But we don\'t have a  central catalog that says that deposit #1234 is stored under  /archival-storage/deposits/1234, on tape, and at  remote-site.icpsr.umich.edu/archival-storage/deposits/1234. One could  build exactly such a catalog, of course, and then create the process to  keep it up to date, but would it have much value? What if all we did was  tell a wrapper around rsync to capture the output and update the  catalog?<br /><br />Probably not.<br /><br />And so if we interpret the TRAC  requirement to build a location register to mean that we should have a  complete, enumerated list of each and every copy, then we don\'t do so  well here. But if we interpret the requirement to mean that we can find a  copy by looking on a list (i.e., the catalog proper) or look at a rule  (i.e., if the master copy is in location x, then two other copies can be  found by applying functions <em>f(x)</em> and <em>g(x)</em>), then we\'re doing pretty well after all.<br /><br />Limitations  in storage systems also add complexity. For instance, I was once  looking at Amazon\'s S3 as a possible location for items in archival  storage. But S3 doesn\'t let me have objects bigger than 5GB, and since I  sometimes have very large files, this means that the record-keeping  would be even more complicated. <em>For an object with name X, you can  find it in this S3 bucket, unless it is bigger than 5GB, in which case  you need to look for N different objects and join them together.</em> Ick.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(301,72,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Workflows; system analysis of how long it takes for copies to  synchronize; procedures/documentation of operating procedures related to  updates and copy synchronization; procedures/documentation related to  whether changes lead to the creation of new copies and how those copies  are propagated and/or linked to previous versions.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.4</strong> Repository has mechanisms in place to ensure any/multiple copies of digital objects are synchronized.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/10/trac-c14-synchronizing-objects.html [BB 10/21/2009]:</p><p>\"I think we have a good story to tell.<br /><br />As  new objects enter Archival Storage at ICPSR, they reside in a  well-known, special-purpose location. Automated, regularly scheduled  system jobs synchronize those objects with remote locations using  standard, established tools such as rsync and other, less common tools  such as Storage Resource Broker (SRB) command-line utilities, such as  Srsync.<br /><br />The output of these system jobs is captured and delivered  nightly to a shared electronic mailbox. The mailbox is reviewed on a  daily basis; this task belongs to the member of the ICPSR IT team who is  currently on-call. When a report is missing or when a report indicates  an error, the problem is escalated to someone who can diagnose and  correct the problem. One common problem, for example, occurs when an  object larger than 2GB enters Archival Storage and the SRB Srsync  utility faults. (SRB limits objects to 2GB.) We then remove this object  from the list of items to be synchronized with SRB.<br /><br />Because the  synchronization process is incremental, it has a very short duration.  However, if we were to need to synchronize ALL content, this takes on  the order of days or even weeks. For example, we recently synchronized a  copy of our Access holdings to a computing instance residing in  Amazon\'s EC2 EU-West region, and we found it took approximately one week  to copy about 500GB. As another example, we recently synchronized a  copy of our Archival Storage (which is much larger than the Access  collection) to a system, which like ICPSR and the University of  Michigan, is connected to Internet2\'s Abilene network, and that took far  less time.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(302,70,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Documents that specify bit error detection and correction mechanisms used; risk analysis; error reports; threat analyses.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.5</strong> Repository has effective mechanisms to detect bit corruption or loss.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/10/trac-c15-detecting-corruption-and-loss.html [BB 10/28/2009]:</p><p>\"For each object in Archival Storage, ICPSR computes a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MD5\">MD5 </a> hash. This \"fingerprint\" is then stored as metadata for each object.<br />Automated  jobs \"prowl\" Archival Storage on a regular basis computing the current  MD5 hash for an object, and comparing it to the stored version. In the  case where the hashes differ, and exception is generated, and this  information is reported to the appropriate staff for diagnosis and  correction.<br /><br />In practice we see very few exceptions such as these,  and the most common cause is a blend of human-error and software  failing to handle the error gracefully.<br /><br />Recovery is quick. In the  event the problem was caused by human-error, and the ctime (last  modified) timestamp has changed, then any copies managed via rsync may  also be damaged, and we instead need to fetch the original object from a  different source (e.g., tape or a copy managed via SRB\'s Srsync). In  the event the problem was caused without ctime also changing, then we  also have the option of fetching an original copy from one of our  rsync-managed copies.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(303,69,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Preservation metadata (e.g., PDI) records; comparison of error logs to  reports to administration; escalation procedures related to data loss.  Trustworthy Repositories Audit &amp; Certification: Criteria and  Checklist</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.6</strong> Repository reports to its administration all incidents  of data corruption or loss, and steps taken to repair/replace corrupt or  lost data.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/11/trac-c16-reporting-and-repairing-loss.html [BB 11/4/2009]:</p><p>\"My  sense is that this requirement is just about policy as it is process.  Fortunately for our data holdings (but unfortunately for TRAC  preparation), data loss or corruption is a very infrequent event, and  therefore as one might expect, the set of policies and written processes  is pretty small.<br /><br />As a point of comparison, if we look at our  policies and processes for handling loss with \"working files\" we will  find a much richer set of policies and systems. We have established  infrastructure (an EMC Network Attached Storage (NAS) storage applicance  and associated Dell tape management solution); we have internal  policies and processes that document how to retrieve lost content; we  have external policies that describe which parts of the NAS are written  to tape, and the schedule of tape backups; and, we exercise the system  on a regular basis as people inadvertently delete or damage files with  which they are working actively.<br /><br />On the Archival Storage side -  or even the Access side, where we also look for loss and corruption -  the number of data loss or data corruption events is very, very low.  Email reports come out on a regular basis, but they always (almost) say  that everything is fine. And on that rare occasion where there is an  issue, the remedy is quick.<br /><br />Perhaps the right solution here is to  use the small sample of issues that have arisen over the years as our  baseline for writing up a process, and then posting that process on our  internal web site. That would be easy to do. But then the concern is  this: If a policy is used very, very infrequently, it is likely to fall  into disrepair. It is also likely to become forgotten. Maybe the tool  that examines for loss or corruption should also contain a link to the  relevant policies and recovery processes?<br /><br />What strategies have others used to address this TRAC requirement?\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(304,68,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Documentation of processes; policies related to hardware support,  maintenance, and replacement; documentation of hardware manufacturers\'  expected support life cycles.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.7</strong> Repository has defined processes for storage media and/or hardware change (e.g., refreshing, migration).</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/11/trac-c17-refreshingmigrating-content.html [BB 11/13/2009]:</p><p>\"ICPSR\'s  archival storage consumes less than 6 TB of storage today. Over the  past month we\'ve made copies in other locations, and the time to copy it  across a network is anywhere from a day to a week, depending upon the  speed of the network. So that\'s much shorter than the lifespan of the  media. :-)<br /><br />The master copy resides on an EMC Celera NAS. From  time to time one of the SATA drives that underpins archival storage will  fail, and the Celera will fail over to its hot spare, and make a phone  call for EMC to schedule a replacement. And, so in some odd way, the  media gets refreshed on an incremental basis slowly over time.<br /><br />We  bought our Celera in 2005, and my expectation is that we\'ll likely  replace it with something else in 2010; 2011 at the very latest. And so  it\'s timely to start thinking about a written procedure for moving the  master copy of the content from the Celera to the next storage platform.  I don\'t think it will be a complicated procedure, and putting it  together might make for a good future post.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(305,66,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Documentation of change management process; comparison of logs of actual  system changes to processes versus associated analyses of their impact  and criticality.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.8</strong> Repository has a documented change management process  that identifies changes to critical processes that potentially affect  the repository\'s ability to comply with its mandatory responsibilities.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/12/trac-c18-change-management.html [BB 12/11/2009]:</p><p>\"Establishing  and following a change management process is a lot like stretching  before working out. We know we should do it, we feel better when we do,  but, wow, is it ever hard to make a point to do it.<br /><br />I\'ve used a  change management process in the past. At ANS Communications we would  only make major configuration changes to the network on certain days and  at certain times, and we would drive the changes from a central  database. This was particularly important when we made a long and very  painful transition away from the NSFnet-era equipment that had formed  our backbone network to new equipment from a company known as Bay  Networks.<br /><br />At ICPSR I think we could use something fairly  straight-forward. There are only a handful of critical software systems,  and they don\'t change that often. We already track software-level  changes in CVS, and we already announce feature-level changes to the  designated community (e.g., ICPSR staff for internal systems), and so we  might pull it all together by linking the announcements with the code  changes in JIRA. I could also imagine a thread on our Intranet (which is  Drupal-based) which could form a central summary of changes: what,  when, how, and links to more details.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(306,64,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C1. System Infrastructure','<p>Documented testing procedures; documentation of results from prior tests and proof of changes made as a result of tests.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C1.9</strong> Repository has a process for testing the effect of critical changes to the system.</h3>',NULL,0,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>-Recent undetected corruptions in the deposit system.</p><p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/12/trac-c19-change-testing.html [BB 12/25/2009]:</p><p>\"When  I arrived at ICPSR in 2002 the same systems were used for both  production services and for new development. In fact, the total number  of systems at ICPSR was very small; for example, a single machine was  our production database machine, our shared \"time sharing\" machine for  UNIX-based data processing, our anonymous ftp server, and pretty much  everything else.<br /><br />Our model is quite different these days. Most of  our software development occurs on the desktop of the programmer, and  new code is rolled out to a staging server for testing and evaluation.  The level and intensity of the testing varies widely at ICPSR; my sense  is that public-facing systems get the most evaluation, and internal-only  systems receive very little. Nonetheless, unless the evaluation reveals  serious flaws, the software is then rolled into production on a fixed  deployment schedule. Because all software resides in a repository, we  can back out changes easily if needed.<br /><br />The last six software  developers we\'ve hired have all worked in the Java environment, and  we\'re in the process of moving our Perl/CGI team to Java as well. My  sense is that getting all of the major systems in Java will make it  easier to use unit-testing tools, like JUnit for example.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(307,61,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C2. Appropriate Technologies','<p>Technology watch; documentation of procedures; designated community profiles; user needs evaluation; hardware inventory.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C2.1</strong> Repository has hardware technologies appropriate to the  services it provides to its designated community(ies) and has procedures  in place to receive and monitor notifications, and evaluate when  hardware technology changes are needed.</h3>','<p>\"Standard Hardware for ICPSR Employees\" (Source: <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edudrupal/1331\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1331</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</p>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/01/trac-c21-appropriate-hardware.html [BB 1/8/2010]:</p><p>\"For  the types of material that ICPSR preserves and delivers to its clients,  hardware selection has been relatively unimportant since the birth and  promulgation of the Web.<br /><br />In ICPSR\'s early days, when it would  send magnetic tapes to its member schools for use on their own campus,  hardware selection, particularly in terms of media types, was a very  important consideration. If most campuses were using, say, IBM labeled  cartridge tapes routinely but ICPSR was sending ANSI labeled 9-track  tapes, this would have imposed an additional burden on our designated  community. However, in a world where the typical access is via a Web  download, the underlying hardware selection - disk, server, router,  switch - just doesn\'t matter all that much.<br /><br />Also, because ICPSR\'s  unit of delivery is relatively small - most of our content is on the  order of megabytes - issues such as network bandwidth are not critical.  In a typical day ICPSR might deliver 20GB of content to hundreds or even  thousands of separate sessions, and so with even modest networking  resources (1 Gb/s NIC, 1 Gb/s switch, 10 Gb/s campus backbone, etc), the  \"pipes\" are more than sufficient to deliver good service.<br /><br />One  interesting area to consider with regard to hardware selection is  virtualization. For example, in some cases it might make more sense for a  depositor to leave ICPSR with an image of a complete computing system  in addition to a dataset. In most cases the deposit contains simple  rectangular data that can be normalized relatively easily into plain  character data and accompanying \"setups\" to make it easy to use with the  most common statistical packages. However, if the dataset were more  complex - say a relational database - then normalizing the data could be  prohibitively expensive, or damaging to the data, or both. In this  case, having a machine image that would contain a host operating system,  the database application, and the user database might be a useful  addition both for preservation and delivery.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(308,59,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C2. Appropriate Technologies','<p>Technology watch; documentation of procedures; designated community profiles; user needs evaluation; software inventory.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3>Repository has software technologies appropriate to the services it  provides to its designated community(ies) and has procedures in place to  receive and monitor notifications, and evaluate when software  technology changes are needed.<a href=\"https://drupal.icpsr.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1911\"></a></h3>','<p>\"Standard Software for ICPSR Employees\" (Source: <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edudrupal/1332\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1332</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</p>',3,NULL,NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/02/trac-c22-appropriate-software.html [BB 2/8/2010]:</p><p>\"My  sense is that ICPSR is very strong in this area, and is, in general,  quite strong in areas that touch the Access portion of the OAIS  framework.<br /><br />Regardless of the format in which it receives content,  and regardless of the internal format used to preserve the content,  ICPSR routinely produces the \"full product suite\" of formats for  delivery on the web site. At this time this includes  platform-independent versions of SPSS, SAS, and Stata, as well as  tab-separate values (for those that might want to use Excel or Access),  and even plain ASCII data with setups.<br /><br />ICPSR also prepares the  content for use with our online analysis systems, SDA from UC Berkeley.  This opens up access to the data for those users who lack statistical  analysis software, and also allows one to subset the data prior to  download.<br /><br />Also, ICPSR spends a considerable amount of resources  on data discovery and data browsing systems, such as our new faceted  search, and the extensive metadata we prepare to document the data.  These too might fall into the \"appropriate software\" portion of TRAC.<br /><br />Does  my sense of how we\'re doing match that of the communities we serve? How  well do you think we\'re doing at providing the right types of access  and appropriate formats?\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(309,57,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C3. Security','<p>ISO 17799 certification; documentation describing analysis and risk  assessments undertaken and their outputs; logs from environmental  recorders; confirmation of successful staff vetting.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C3.1</strong> Repository maintains a systematic analysis of such factors as data, systems, personnel, physical plant, and security needs.</h3>',NULL,NULL,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/02/trac-c31-risk-assessment.html [BB 2/12/2010]:</p><p>\"ICPSR performs regular risk assessment using a variety of techniques.<br /><br />One,  on a purely technological level, ICPSR analyzes its security exposure  through regular vulnerability scans that are conducted by the <a href=\"http://safecomputing.umich.edu/\">University of Michigan\'s Information Technology Security Services</a> (ITSS) team. This includes participation in a mandatory, quarterly,  campus-wide scan, and also an optional, monthly, detailed scan of our  own network.<br /><br />Two, ICPSR and its parent organization, the <a href=\"http://www.isr.umich.edu/home/\">Institute for Social Research</a> (ISR), undergo periodic Information Technology audits that are conducted by the <a href=\"http://www.umich.edu/%7Euaudits/\">University of Michigan\'s Office of University Audits</a> . These are comprehensive assessments of physical and electronic security.<br /><br />Three,  ICPSR and its parent organization, ISR, conduct two risk evaluation  projects each year to assess risks and vulnerabilities in IT  infrastructure. The most recent one undertaken by ICPSR was in 2009, and  the focus was on research data security.<br /><br />Four, again, ICPSR along with ISR, participate in an <a href=\"http://www.safecomputing.umich.edu/ITProfessionals.php\">annual review and refresh of an organization-wide IT security plan</a> . This is a comprehensive evaluation of vulnerabilities, strengths, and  resources related to security, and flows into a University of Michigan  central repository of security plans, and is also reviewed by the  leadership of ISR.<br /><br />Five, ICPSR also participated in the Center  for Research Libraries Auditing and Certification of Digital Archives  Project \"test audit\" in 2005-2006. This audit reviewed a broad spectrum  of functions and services at ICPSR (including IT), and produced a <a href=\"http://www.crl.edu/sites/default/files/attachments/pages/ICPSR_final.pdf\">publicly available report</a> . The report was very favorable to ICPSR:</p><blockquote><p><em>Auditors  found an organization with a mature, fully operational archive. ICPSR  as an organization has a 44-year history of growing and managing a large  (at the time of the audit 2.3 Terabytes) data archive of valuable  content with a virtually unblemished record in data management and  access. The future prospects of both the organization and the data  appear favorable, due to a combination of sound financial management and  planning, multiple sources of revenue, robust reporting and  accountability mechanisms, and sound technical decisions related to  processes, procedures, and formats.<br /></em></p></blockquote><p>In  summary, ICPSR conducts risk assessment - particularly technological  risk assessment - in a variety of ways on a routine basis.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(310,55,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C3. Security','<p>ISO 17799 certification; system control list; risk, threat, or control  analyses; addition of controls based on ongoing risk detection and  assessment.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C3.2</strong> Repository has implemented controls to adequately address each of the defined security needs.</h3>','<p>\"ICPSR IT Security and Backups\" (Source: <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edudrupal/1362\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1362</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</p>',1,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>-Status of \"Cyber Incident Response Plan\" (Source: <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edudrupal/1417\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1417</a>)?</p><p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/02/trac-c32-security-controls.html&nbsp; [BB 2/19/2010]:</p><p>\"Broadly  speaking ICPSR has only two types of objects to manage: (1) those that  have been reviewed and vetted, and are available for wide dissemination,  and (2) everything else.<br /><br />The first category of objects require  relatively modest security controls. Because this content is freely  available via our web site (albeit some only to members) there are  relatively few concerns about its security. It\'s important that we know  that the objects haven\'t been corrupted (unintentionally or otherwise),  and it\'s also important to ensure that member-only content is accessible  only to members.<br /><br />The second category has grown considerably in  the past few years, particularly as ICPSR receives more confidential  data through government agencies, partners, and unsolicited via its  deposit system.<br /><br />To meet the rising challenge of confidential data  ICPSR will be changing the architecture of its network, and will also  be deploying a Secure Data processing Environment. (More on the SDE in a  subsequent post.) Both of these steps supplement existing security  controls that we discussed in the post <a href=\"http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/09/icpsr-web-site-and-security.html\">The ICPSR Web Site and Security</a> from September 2009.<br /><br />Our  current network architecture is very flat. All network-connected  equipment is part of a single virtual local area network (VLAN), and  items are protected at the border between ICPSR and the outside world  via Cisco access-list policies. Individual systems may also be protected  via local firewalls, such as iptables on a Linux server. And equipment  located in Amazon\'s cloud is protected via similar mechanisms using AWS  EC2 Security Groups.<br /><br />Our new network architecture will look very different, and will consist of four separate VLANs. Here is the overall picture:</p><p>http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_2WmjUV0qSjA/S3mRnNlbz0I/AAAAAAAAAMw/uW4qtF0VNH0/s1600-h/ICPSR+LAN+with+VFW.png<br /><br />This  new architecture makes use of a new security service provided by the  University of Michigan\'s central IT organization, ITS. The service is  called Virtual Firewall, and is based on the Checkpoint firewall  product.<br /><br />This architecture divides ICPSR\'s network-connected resources into four VLANs:<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. Public<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. Semi-private<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 3. Private (local to ICPSR)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; 4. Private (local to ITS)<br /><br />The  Public VLAN hosts ICPSR\'s public-facing resources, such as the web  server. This is a relatively small VLAN, and one can imagine resources  moving from this VLAN into Amazon\'s cloud over time. (In fact, a  multi-region delivery platform stretched across Amazon\'s international  cloud, perhaps using AWS CloudFront to deliver especially high-volume  objects is very compelling.)<br /><br />The Semi-private VLAN hosts the bulk  of ICPSR\'s current systems: desktop computers, printers, storage  systems, and so on. This equipment needs robust outbound access to the  Internet, but inbound access should be restricted closely. For example,  there is no good reason why ICPSR\'s printers need to be accessible from  any arbitrary host on the Internet.<br /><br />The Private VLANs will host  our most secure systems. This will include the Secure Data processing  Environment (SDE) we\'re building, and also a future Virtual Data Enclave  (VDE). Access between these VLANs and the Internet will be highly,  highly restricted, and more general access will be permitted only from  our Semi-private VLAN.<br /><br />We\'ve just started the process of building  out this future network architecture with ITS, and expect that we\'ll  finish the deployment and transition before the end of the summer.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(311,53,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C3. Security','<p>ISO 17799 certification; organizational chart; system authorization documentation.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C3.3</strong> Repository staff have delineated roles, responsibilities, and authorizations related to implementing changes within the system.</h3>',NULL,3,'Not Done',NULL,'<p>-Systems authorization documentation?</p><p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/02/trac-c33-roles-responsibilities-and.html [BB 2/23/2010]:</p><p>\"ICPSR  is a very mature organization, and experiences very low staff  turnover  and very little of the reorganizations, mergers, and other   organizational changes one finds in the for-profit world.  Roles and   responsibilities are known well, and the knowledge is common across work   groups.  We don\'t often hire completely new types of positions, and so   when we do hire a new employee, they tend to slot easily into an   existing category of employee (e.g., \"data processor\").<br /><br />The   combination of a category, or role, and the specific work group - such   as, the new hire, Jane, is a Data Processor in SAMHDA - translate easily   into a set of related technology containers such as Active Directory   groups, LDAP groups, old school UNIX /etc/group entries, and even our   own custom database that maps people to groups.<br /><br />My sense is that   the net effect is that we have roles that are well understood, but not   crisply defined; and we have containers to hold the roles, but those   containers are as idiosyncratic as the collection of technology we use   to drive ICPSR.\"</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(312,51,'C. Technologies, Technical Infrastructure &amp; Security','C3. Security','<p>ISO 17799 certification; disaster and recovery plans; information about  and proof of at least one off-site copy of preserved information;  service continuity plan; documentation linking roles with activities;  local geological, geographical, or meteorological data or threat  assessments.</p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<h3><strong>C3.4</strong> Repository has suitable written disaster preparedness  and recovery plan(s), including at least one off-site backup of all  preserved information together with an off-site copy of the recovery  plan(s).</h3>','<p>\"Disaster Planning at ICPSR\" (Source: <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edudrupal/1417\" target=\"_blank\">https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSR/node/1417</a>) [JAL, 7/20/2009]</p>',3,'Evidence Proposed',NULL,'<p>From http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2010/03/trac-c34-disaster-preparedness.html [BB 3/5/2010]:</p><p>\"Building  and documenting systems and procedures for coping with a  disaster has a  scope well beyond just IT.  But there are two key areas  worth  discussing that fall within the purview of IT.<br /><br />One area is   ensuring that ICPSR is able to deliver its content to its clients,   members, and the public at all time.  This is an area where we\'ve made   significant investments over the past twelve months, and where we also   now have a good story to tell.<br /><br />The main ICPSR delivery mechanism   is its web site.  The technological resources that power the primary   instance of the web site reside at ICPSR itself on the campus of the   University of Michigan.  This consists of three mains systems:  a   reasonably powerful server running web applications; another powerful   server running an Oracle database; and our storage appliance.<br /><br />Our   equipment resides in an eclectic machine room.  On the plus side it  has  items one would expect to find like equipment cabinets, local air   handlers providing chilled air, and UPS to protect us from power   fluctuations.  On the negative side there is no raised floor or cable   trays, which makes for a messy machine room, and our connection to Ann   Arbor\'s (not U-M\'s) electrical grid is somewhat precarious.  An off-site   network operations center monitors our gear 24 x 7 and notifies us via   SMS, pager, and telephone if anything looks broken.<br /><br />We maintain  a  replica of our web environment in Amazon\'s cloud, and we use a  simple  mechanism to trigger a failover to the replica:  The oncall  technician  changes the DNS record for www.icpsr.umich.edu to point to  the replica  instead of the primary.  The time-to-live on the record is  low (five  minutes), and so once the process has been followed, failover  is quick.   (And the change is made on a \"stealth\" DNS server that also  lives in  Amazon\'s cloud.)<br /><br />And, finally, we synchronize the replica several times throughout the workday so that software and content is always fresh.<br /><br />This   setup doesn\'t create a web environment which promises \"five nines\"  type  of uptime (i.e., 99.999% availability), but it does give us the   capability to avoid any long multi-day outage like we saw late in 2008,   and it also gives us the capability to deliver content indefinitely  from  the replica should ICPSR stuffer a disaster.<br /><br />The second  main  area where IT plays a key role is with archival storage.  This is  less  about 24 x 7 availability, and more about ensuring that our  archival  holdings are available for long-term access in a robust  storage fabric.<br /><br />A <a href=\"http://techaticpsr.blogspot.com/2009/11/icpsr-content-and-availability.html\">post from November 2009</a> is still an accurate depiction of how we replicate our archival   holdings so that we can be guaranteed to have a copy even if something   catastrophic happens to our main location in Ann Arbor.  I\'m also   interested in deploying copies outside the United States.  We\'ve had   some very useful conversations with colleagues at the <a href=\"http://anusf.anu.edu.au/\">ANU Supercomputer Facility</a> in Australia, and perhaps some sort of reciprocal storage arrangement might be worked out.\"&nbsp;</p>',1,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,1),(313,3,'A. Organizational Structure','A1. Governance &amp; Organizational Viability','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">Succession plan(s); escrow plan(s); explicit and specific statement documenting the intent to ensure continuity of the repository, and the steps taken and to be taken to ensure continuity; formal documents describing exit strategies and contingency plans; depositor agreements.</span></p>','<p>See <a href=\"https://webservices.itcs.umich.edu/drupal/ICPSRTRAC/node/86\">ICPSR Responsibilities for TRAC</a> for an explanation and details.</p>','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\"> </span></p><h3 style=\"font-weight: normal; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; padding: 0px; margin: 0px;\"><strong>A1.2</strong> Repository has an appropriate, formal succession plan, contingency plans, and/or escrow arrangements in place in case the repository ceases to operate or the governing or funding institution substantially changes its scope.</h3><p>&nbsp;</p>','<p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">Data-PASS partnership agreement: \"In the event that one of the partner institutions should no longer be able to retain the material they acquire, it will be transferred to one of the other partners. Both the original material and any additional material derived from the originals will be transferred.\" (Data-PASS Articles of Collaboration;<a title=\"https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/DATAPASS/pdf/collaboration.pdf\" href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/files/DATAPASS/pdf/collaboration.pdf\" style=\"color: #027ac6; text-decoration: none;\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/files/DATAPASS/pdf/collaboration.pdf</a>) [Collection Development (Jared Lyle), 7/20/2009].  The Data-PASS steering committee has drafted a more recent and comprehensive partnership agreement that is circulating for signature.   [Digital Preservation, 23 March 2011]</span></p><p><span style=\"color: #494949; font-family: Verdana; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;\">The Data-PASS partners are the most logical possible successors should ICPSR no longer be able to carry out its mission as a social science data archive.  The Data-PASS policies, agreements, and expectations are well-documented : <a href=\"http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/DATAPASS/best-practices.jsp \"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #800080;\">http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/DATAPASS/best-practices.jsp</span></span></a> </span></p>',4,'Action Item(s)','<p>Enter the <span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span>link to the more recent Data-PAS<span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> <span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span></span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span>S<span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; display: none;\" id=\"_mce_start\"> </span><span style=\"line-height: 0; d