INSERT INTO `taxonomy_term_data` VALUES (1,2,'Not started','','filtered_html',3),(2,2,'In progress','','filtered_html',2),(3,2,'Ready for review','','filtered_html',1),(4,2,'Accepted','','filtered_html',0),(5,3,'3. Organizational Infrastructure','','plain_text',0),(6,3,'4. Digital Object Management','','plain_text',1),(7,3,'5. Infrastructure and Security Risk Management','','plain_text',2),(8,3,'3.1 Governance and Organizational Viability','','plain_text',0),(9,3,'3.2 Organizational Structure and Staffing','','plain_text',1),(10,3,'3.3 Procedural Accountability and Preservation Policy Framework','<p>Documentation assures stakeholders (consumers, producers, and contributors of digital content) that the repository is meeting its requirements and fully performing its role as a trustworthy digital repository. A repository must create documentation that reflects its Mission Statement and Strategic Plan and captures its normal activities. This entails documenting all repository processes, decision-making, and goal setting. Documentation is provided so that the activities of the repository will be understood by stakeholders and management. It ensures that repository policies and procedures are carried out in approved, consistent ways, resulting in long-term preservation and access to digital content in its care. Certification, the clearest indicator of a repository’s sound and standards-based practice, is facilitated by procedural accountability and documentation.</p>','plain_text',2),(11,3,'3.4 Financial Sustainability','','plain_text',3),(12,3,'3.5 Contracts, Licenses and Liabilities','','plain_text',4),(13,3,'4.1 Ingest: Acquisition of Content','','plain_text',0),(14,3,'4.2 Ingest: Creation of the AIP','','plain_text',1),(15,3,'4.3 Preservation Planning','','plain_text',2),(16,3,'4.4 AIP Preservation','','plain_text',3),(17,3,'4.5 Information Management','','plain_text',4),(18,3,'4.6 Access Management','<p>The term ‘access’ has a number of different senses, including access by users to the repository system, for example, physical security and user authentication, and the different stages of accessing records (making a request, verifying the rights of the requester, and preparing and sending a Dissemination Information Package [DIP]). This subsection is concerned with all of these. It is divided into two main requirements, one concerned with the existence and implementation of access policies, and one with the capacity of the repository to provide demonstrably authentic objects as DIPs. Thus the first requirement relates to requests initiated by a user and how the repository handles them to ensure that rights and<br />agreements are respected, that security is monitored, that requests are fulfilled, etc. The second requirement relates to what is delivered to the Consumer and the trust that can be placed in it.</p><p>It must be understood that the capabilities and sophistication of the access system will vary depending on the repository’s Designated Community and the access mandates of the repository. Because of the variety of repositories and access mandates, these criteria may be subject to questions about applicability and interpretation at a local level.</p>','plain_text',5),(19,3,'5.1 Technical Infrastructure Risk Management','','plain_text',0),(20,3,'5.2 Security Risk Management','','plain_text',1),(21,4,'Senior Management','','filtered_html',0),(22,4,'Coordination Group','','filtered_html',1),(23,4,'Operations Group','','filtered_html',2),(24,4,'Information Technology','','filtered_html',3),(25,4,'Administration: Finance or HR','','filtered_html',4),(26,4,'Acquisitions','','filtered_html',5),(27,4,'Preservation','','filtered_html',6),(28,4,'Dissemination','','filtered_html',7),(29,4,'Rights Management','','filtered_html',8),(30,4,'External Advisory Group','','filtered_html',9),(31,5,'Responsible','Person or group who performs an activity or does the work','filtered_html',0),(32,5,'Accountable','Person or group who is ultimate